# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battering-ram
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The **11th Dynasty** of ancient Egypt (notated **Dynasty XI**; c.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] 1991 BC) is a well-attested group of rulers.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Its earlier members before King Mentuhotep II are grouped with the four preceding dynasties to form the First Intermediate Period, whereas the later members are considered part of the Middle Kingdom.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] They all ruled from Thebes in Upper Egypt.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The relative chronology of the 11th Dynasty is well established by contemporary attestations and, except for count Intef and Mentuhotep IV, by the Turin canon.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Manetho's statement that the 11th Dynasty consisted of 16 kings, who reigned for 43 years is contradicted by contemporary inscriptions and the evidence of the Turin King List, whose combined testimony establishes that this kingdom consisted of seven kings who ruled for a total of 143 years.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] However, his testimony that this dynasty was based at Thebes is verified by the contemporary evidence.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] It was during this dynasty that all of ancient Egypt was united under the Middle Kingdom.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] This dynasty traces its origins to a nomarch of Thebes, "Intef the Great, son of Iku", who is mentioned in a number of contemporary inscriptions.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] However, his immediate successor Mentuhotep I is considered the first king of this dynasty.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] An inscription carved during the reign of Wahankh Intef II shows that he was the first of this dynasty to claim to rule over the whole of Egypt, a claim which brought the Thebans into conflict with the 10th-Dynasty rulers of Herakleopolis Magna.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Intef undertook several campaigns northwards, and captured the important nome of Abydos.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Warfare continued intermittently between the Theban and Heracleapolitan dynasts until shortly before the 39th regnal year of Nebhepetre Mentuhotep II, when the Herakleopolitans were defeated, and this dynasty could begin to consolidate their rule.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The rulers of the 11th Dynasty reasserted Egypt's influence over her neighbors in Africa and the Near East.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Mentuhotep II sent renewed expeditions to Phoenicia to obtain cedar.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Sankhkare Mentuhotep III sent an expedition from Coptos south to the land of Punt.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The reign of its last king, and thus the end of this dynasty, is something of a mystery.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Contemporary records refer to "seven empty years" following the death of Mentuhotep III, which correspond to the reign of Nebtawyre Mentuhotep IV.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Modern scholars identify his vizier Amenemhat with Amenemhat I, the first king of 12th Dynasty, as part of a theory that Amenemhat became king as part of a palace coup.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The only certain details of Mentuhotep's reign was that two remarkable omens were witnessed at the quarry of Wadi Hammamat by the vizier Amenemhat.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Nobody knows for certain how Amenemhat I rose to power and became the next king.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Kings Mentuhotep II and Mentuhotep III are the most commonly included kings of this dynasty to appear on Egyptian king lists, while their successor Mentuhotep IV was often ignored.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Several names are lost and damaged, but can still be reconstructed.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] The Turin King List begins this dynasty with Mentuhotep I and provides reign lengths for individual kings, however it is in a fragmentary state and some information is now lost.
[src:battering-ram/11th-dynasty] Mentuhotep IV is not mentioned at all, but the list does note "a lacuna of 7 years" following Mentuhotep III.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Long before the invention of aircraft, ramming tactics in naval warfare and ground warfare were common.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The first aerial ramming was performed by Pyotr Nesterov in 1914 during the First World War.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In the early stages of World War II the tactic was employed by Soviet pilots, who called it ***taran (таран)*** , the Russian word for 'ramming" and "battering ram".
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] A ramming pilot could use the weight of the aircraft as a ram, or they could try to make the enemy lose control of their plane, using the propeller or wing to damage the enemy's tail or wing.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ramming took place when a pilot ran out of ammunition yet was still intent on destroying an enemy, or when the plane had already been damaged beyond saving.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Most rammings occurred when the attacker's aircraft was economically, strategically or tactically less valuable than the enemy's, such as pilots flying obsolescent aircraft against superior ones, or one man risking his life to kill multiple men.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Defending forces resorted to ramming more often than the attackers.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] A ramming attack was not considered suicidal in the same manner as *kamikaze* attacks—the ramming pilot stood a chance of surviving, though it was very risky.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Sometimes the ramming aircraft itself could survive to make a controlled landing, though most were lost due to combat damage or the pilot bailing out.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ramming was used in air warfare in the first half of the 20th century, in both World Wars and in the interwar period.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] With jet aircraft, as air combat speeds increased, ramming became disused—the probability of successfully executing (and surviving) a ramming attack approached zero.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] However, the tactic is still possible in modern warfare.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The first two options were always premeditated but required a high level of piloting skill.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The last option might be premeditated or it might be a snap decision made during combat; either way it often killed the attacking pilot.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Presaging the 20th century air warfare ramming actions, Jules Verne imagined an apparent aerial attack made by a heavy flying machine with a prominent ram prow against a nearly defenseless lighter-than-air craft in his science fiction work *Robur the Conqueror*, published in 1886.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Wells, writing in 1899 in his novel *The Sleeper Awakes*, has his main character, Graham, ram one of the enemy's aeroplanes with his flying apparatus, causing it to fall out of the sky.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] A second enemy machine ceases its attack, afraid of being rammed in turn.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The first known instance of ramming in air warfare was made over Zhovkva by the Russian pilot Pyotr Nesterov on 8 September 1914, against an Austrian plane.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Nesterov's Morane-Saulnier Type G (s/n 281) and the Austrian Albatros B.II reconnaissance aircraft both crashed in the ramming, killing Nesterov and both occupants of the Austrian aircraft.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The second ramming—and the first successful ramming that was not fatal to the attacker—was performed in 1915 by Alexander Kazakov, a flying ace and the most successful Russian fighter pilot of World War I.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Sgt Arturo Dell'Oro of the Italian 83rd Squadron rammed a two-man Br.C.1 of Flik 45 on 1 September 1917.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The American Wilbert Wallace White of the 147th Aero Squadron rammed a German plane on 10 October 1918, and was killed — his opponent survived.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] As the advancing Soviet Red Army used very few aircraft in Poland, air combat rarely took place (except for interceptions of Bolshevik observation balloons).
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] However, during the course of the war, several Polish pilots, having depleted their ammunition and bombs, attempted to ram Soviet cavalry with their aircraft's undercarriages.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] This attack allowed an opportunity for an emergency landing, but it almost always ended with the destruction of, or serious damage to, the ramming aircraft.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ramming was used in the Spanish Civil War.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On the night of 27–28 November 1937, Soviet pilot Evgeny Stepanov, flying a Polikarpov I-15 for the Spanish Republican Air Force, shot down one SM.81 bomber near Barcelona and emptied the rest of his ammunition into another.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The second SM.81 continued to fly, so Stepanov resorted to using the left leg of his Chaika's undercarriage to ram the bomber, downing the plane.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In World War II, reports of ramming by lone Soviet pilots against the *Luftwaffe* became widespread, especially in the early days of the hostilities in the war's Eastern Front.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In the first year of the Great Patriotic War, most available Soviet machines were markedly inferior to the German ones and pilots sometimes perceived a *taran* as the only way to guarantee the destruction of the enemy.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Early Soviet fighter engines were relatively weak, and the underpowered fighters were either fairly well-armed but too slow, or fast but too lightly armed.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Lightly armed fighters often expended their ammunition without bringing down the enemy bomber.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Very few fighters had radios installed—the pilots had no way to call for assistance and the military expected them to solve problems alone.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Trading a single fighter for a multi-engine bomber was considered economically sound.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In some cases, pilots who were heavily wounded or in damaged aircraft decided to perform a suicidal attack against air, ground or naval targets.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In this instance, the attack becomes more like an unpremeditated *kamikaze* attack (see Nikolai Gastello).
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] German air tactics early in the war changed in a way that created conditions ripe for ramming attacks.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After clearing much of Soviet airpower from their path, the Luftwaffe stopped providing fighter escort for bombing groups, and split their forces into much smaller sorties, including single aircraft making deep penetration flights.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] One quarter of German aircraft on the Eastern Front had the task of performing strategic or tactical reconnaissance with their *Aufklärungsgruppe* units.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] These reconnaissance or long-range bombing flights were more likely to encounter lone Soviet defenders.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Soviet group tactics did not include *taran*, but Soviet fighters often sortied singly or in pairs rather than in groups.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Soviet pilots were prohibited from performing *taran* over enemy-held land, but could ram enemy reconnaissance penetrations over the homeland.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Nine rammings took place on the very first day of the German invasion of the Soviet Union, one within the first hour.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] At 0425 hours on 22 June 1941, Lieutenant Ivan Ivanov supposedly drove his Polikarpov I-16 into the tail of an invading Heinkel He 111.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ivanov did not survive but was posthumously awarded the Gold Star medal, Hero of the Soviet Union.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Yekaterina Zelenko on 12 September 1941 supposedly performed a diving ramming attack in her Su-2, which tore a Messerschmitt Bf 109 in two as the propeller of her plane hit the German aircraft's tail.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] She remains the only woman ever alleged to have performed an aerial ramming.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After 1943 more Soviet fighters had radios installed, and Chief Marshall Alexander Novikov developed air-control techniques to coordinate attacks.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The fighters had more powerful engines, and in the last year of battle they carried sufficiently heavy armament.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] As Soviet air-attack options improved, ramming became a rare occurrence.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In 1944, future Air Marshall Alexander Pokryshkin officially discouraged the *taran*, limiting it to "exceptional instances and as an extreme measure".
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Lieutenant Boris Kovzan supposedly survived a record four ramming attacks in the war.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Aleksei Khlobystov supposedly made three.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Seventeen other Soviet pilots were credited with two successful ramming attacks.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] According to new research, at least 636 successful *taran* attacks were made by Soviets between the beginning of Operation Barbarossa and the end of the war.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Of these, 227 pilots were killed during the attack or afterwards (35.7%), 233 landed safely, and the rest bailed out.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] As new Soviet fighter designs went into service, ramming was discouraged.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The economics had shifted; now the Soviet fighter was roughly equivalent to the German one.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] By September 1944, orders describing how and when to initiate the ramming attack were removed from training materials.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 18 August 1940, Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve Sergeant Bruce Hancock of No.6 SFTS from RAF Windrush used his Avro Anson aircraft to ram a Heinkel He 111P; there were no survivors.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On the same day Flight Lieutenant James Eglington Marshall of No.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 85 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to ram the tail unit of a Heinkel He 111 after he had expended the last of his ammunition on it.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The Hurricane's starboard wing tip broke off in the attack and the Heinkel was assessed as "probably destroyed".
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] A significant event took place during the Battle of Britain.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 504 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to destroy a Dornier Do 17 bomber over London by ramming but at the loss of his own aircraft (and almost his own life) in one of the defining moments of the Battle of Britain.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Holmes, making a head-on attack, found his guns inoperative.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] He flew his plane into the top-side of the German bomber, cutting off the rear tail section with his wing and causing the bomber to dive out of control and crash.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Its pilot, Oberleutnant Robert Zehbe, bailed out, only to die later of wounds suffered during the attack, while the injured Holmes bailed out of his plane and survived.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Two other crewmen of the Dornier bailed out and survived.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] As the RAF did not practice ramming as an air combat tactic, this was considered an impromptu manoeuvre, and an act of selfless courage.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] This event became one of the defining moments of the Battle of Britain and elicited a congratulatory note to the RAF from Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands, who had witnessed the event.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 27 September 1940, Flying Officer Percival R.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 249 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to tear off the tail unit of a Messerschmitt Bf 110 of V/LG 1.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] According to eyewitnesses on the ground, Burton deliberately rammed the Bf 110 after a "wildly manoeuvring" chase at rooftop height over Hailsham, England.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Burton, Hauptmann Horst Liensberger and Unteroffizier Albert Kopge were all killed when both aircraft crashed just outside town.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Burton's Hurricane was found exhausted of ammunition.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 501 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to destroy a Messerschmitt Bf 109.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 11 November 1940, Flight Lieutenant Howard Peter Blatchford (Canadian) of No.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 257 Squadron RAF used the propeller of his Hawker Hurricane to attack a Fiat CR.42 near Harwich, England.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Blatchford had used up his ammunition during a mêlée with Italian fighters, and upon returning to base discovered two of his propeller blades missing nine inches.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Although he did not see the results of his attack and only claimed the Italian fighter as "damaged", he did report splashes of blood on his damaged propeller.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Although technically not ramming, RAF pilots did use an intentional collision of sorts against the V-1 flying bomb.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] When it was discovered that shooting a V-1 could detonate the warhead and/or fuel tank, thereby endangering the attacking aircraft, pilots would instead fly beside the V-1.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Once in position, the pilot would roll to one side, lifting his wingtip to produce an area of high-pressure turbulence beneath the wingtip of the V-1, causing it to roll in the opposite direction.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] This tactic was known amongst pilots as *wing tipping/wing wacking*.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The rudimentary automatic pilot of the V-1 was often not able to compensate, sending it diving into the ground.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 2 November 1940, Greek pilot Marinos Mitralexis shot down one Italian Savoia-Marchetti SM.79 bomber; then, out of ammunition, brought another down by smashing its rudder with the propeller of his PZL P.24 fighter.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Both aircraft were forced into emergency landings, and Mitralexis threatened the bomber's four-man crew into surrender using his pistol.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Mitralexis was promoted in rank and awarded medals.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The Japanese also practised *tai-atari* ramming, both by individual initiative and by policy.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Individual initiative saw a Nakajima Ki-43 fighter plane bringing down a lone B-17 Flying Fortress, *The Fighting Swede*, on 8 May 1943.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After three of the Japanese fighters had each made two attack passes without decisive results, the bomber's pilot, Major Robert N.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Keatts, made for the shelter of a nearby rain-squall.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Tadao Oda executed a head-on ramming attack, known as taiatari (体当たり, *tai-atari*; "body strike").
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Both aircraft crashed with no survivors.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Oda was posthumously promoted to lieutenant for his sacrifice.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 26 March 1943, Lieutenant Sanae Ishii of the 64th Sentai used the wing of his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram the tail of a Bristol Beaufighter, bringing it down over Shwebandaw, Burma, killing both Squadron Leader Ivan G.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Statham AFC and Pilot Officer Kenneth C.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 1 May 1943 Sergeant Miyoshi Watanabe of the 64th Sentai knocked out two engines of a B-24 Liberator piloted by Robert Kavanaugh, killing two of the bombers crew; he then used his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram the rear turret of the American bomber after a drawn-out battle over Rangoon.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Watanabe survived the attack, as did the remaining B-24 crew.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Both planes made a forced landing without further loss of life.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The crashed B-24 was photographed and appeared in the December 1943 Japanese aviation magazine *Koku Asahi*.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Only three of Kavanaugh's crew survived the war under harsh conditions as POWs.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 26 October 1943 Corporal Tomio Kamiguchi of the 64th Sentai used his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram a B-24J Liberator, when his guns failed to fire during a sustained attack lasting over 50 minutes by Ki-43II and Kawasaki Ki-45s of 21st Sentai.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The engagement included approximately 50 two-ship passes on the B-24s after they attacked Rangoon.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Nearing the Bay of Bengal and already heavily damaged by the other Japanese fighters in the 64th, the bomber, named "Boogie Woogie Bomb Buggy," belonging to the 492nd Bomb Squadron and piloted by 1st Lt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Vaughan, crashed in the jungle approaching Gwa Bay.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Gustaf 'Gus' Johnston was the sole survivor of the B-24 and became a POW.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Kamiguchi was thrown clear in the impact, parachuted, and also survived.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] American researcher Matthew Poole notes that Japanese historian Hiroshi Ichimura interviewed 64th Sentai veteran Lt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Naoyuki Ito, who also claimed to have shot down a B-24 of the 492nd BS on 26 October 1943.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The B-24 was claimed to have been shot down by two experienced Japanese aces: Lt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In addition, Ito stated that 19-year-old green pilot Cpl.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Kamiguchi rammed the crippled B-24, and General Major Shinichi Tanaka praised the brave young pilot and intentionally made "Corporal Saw" a legend.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Major Takuwa said to him "The B-24 was going down.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Shores in *Japanese Army Air Force Fighter Units and Their Aces 1939–1945* includes the biography of Capt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ito of the 64th Sentai which states: “He later transferred to the 3rd Chutai, and was to claim eight victories, including a B-24 over Rangoon on 26 October 1943.” According to Ichimura, Sgt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Takuwa's account was not included in this source, as only aces with nine or more victories were given a biography in the book.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 6 June 1944, having expended his ammunition in an extended dogfight, Sergeant Tomesaku Igarashi of the 50th Sentai used the propeller of his Nakajima Ki-43 to bring down a Lockheed P-38 Lightning near Meiktila, Burma.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After the pilot bailed out, Igarashi attacked him in his parachute.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Shinobu Ikeda of the 25th Dokuritsu Chutai rammed his Ki-45 into Cpt.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Roger Parrish's B-29 "Gallopin Goose" (42-6390) on 7 December over Mukden.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Ikeda and all except one crew member of the B-29 perished.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Starting in August 1944, several Japanese pilots flying Kawasaki Ki-45 and other fighters engaging B-29 Superfortresses found that ramming the very heavy bomber was a practical tactic.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] From that experience, in November 1944 a "Special Attack Unit" was formed using Kawasaki Ki-61s that had been stripped of most of their weapons and armor so as to quickly achieve high altitude.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Three successful surviving ramming pilots were the first recipients of the *Bukosho*, Japan's equivalent to the Victoria Cross or Medal of Honor, an award which had been inaugurated on 7 December 1944 as an Imperial Edict by Emperor Hirohito.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Membership in the Special Attack Unit was seen as a final assignment; the pilots were expected to perform ramming attacks until death or serious injury stopped their service.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The Japanese practice of kamikaze may also be viewed as a form of ramming, although the primary mode of destruction was not physical impact force, but rather the explosives carried.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Kamikaze was used exclusively against Allied ship targets.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Two rammings (Bulgarian: Таран, romanized: *taran*) were performed by Bulgarian fighter pilots defending Sofia against Allied bombers in 1943 and 1944.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The first one was by poruchik (Senior Lieutenant) Dimitar Spisarevski on 20 December 1943.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Flying a Bf 109 G2 fighter, he rammed and destroyed American B-24 Liberator #42-73428 of the 376th Bomb Group, though it is unknown whether the collision was intentional.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The Bulgarian military said it was deliberate, and increased his rank posthumously.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The second ramming was performed by poruchik Nedelcho Bonchev on 17 April 1944 against an American B-17 Flying Fortress.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Bonchev succeeded in bailing out and surviving after the ramming.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After the fall of the Third Bulgarian Kingdom 9 September 1944 he went on flying against the Germans.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] His Bf 109 was shot down during a mission and he was wounded and taken captive.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] After several months in captivity, he was killed by a female SS guard during a POW march which he could not take, owing to his critical health condition.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 22 February 1944 a Messerschmitt Bf 109 rammed B-17 231377 of the 327th Bombardment Squadron.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 25 May 1944 Oberfähnrich Hubert Heckmann used his Messerschmitt Bf 109 to ram a P-51 Mustang when his guns malfunctioned, severing the tail and rear fuselage from the American aircraft.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Bennett of the 336th Fighter Squadron managed to bail out to captivity, while Heckmann made an immediate belly landing near Botenheim, Germany.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 7 July 1944 Unteroffizier Willi Reschke used his Messerschmitt Bf 109 to ram a Consolidated B-24 Liberator when his guns malfunctioned.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The two falling aircraft were locked together, and it was some time before Reschke was able to free himself and bail out near Malacky, Slovakia.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Late in World War II, the Luftwaffe used ramming to try to regain control of the air.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The plan was to dissuade Allied bomber pilots from conducting bombing raids long enough for the Germans to create a significant number of Messerschmitt Me 262 jet fighters to turn the tide of the air war.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 4 April 1945 Heinrich Ehrler rammed a B-24 and was killed.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Only a single dedicated unit, *Sonderkommando Elbe*, was ever formed to the point of being operational, and flew their only mission – only a month before the end of the war in Europe – on 7 April 1945.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Although some pilots succeeded in destroying bombers, Allied numbers were not significantly reduced.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Perhaps the most famous example of aerial ramming carried out by *Elbe* that resulted in the pilot surviving ramming their plane during this mission was that of Heinrich Rosner's Bf 109 vs.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] B-24 44-49533 "Palace of Dallas", which was leading a formation of B-24s of the 389th Bombardment Group at the time.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Rosner's plane sliced through the cockpit of "Palace of Dallas" with its wing, destroying the bomber and crippling the Bf-109, which then collided with an additional unidentified B-24.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Rosner was able to successfully bail out and parachute to safety.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Projects of aircraft such as the Gotha and Zeppelin Rammjäger concepts were intended to use the ramming technique.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 3 August 1944, Captain Jean Maridor of No.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 91 Squadron RAF used his Supermarine Spitfire to ram a V-1 flying bomb, killing himself when the warhead detonated.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Capitaine Maridor had previously damaged the V-1 with his cannon fire, and seeing it begin to dive onto a military field hospital in Kent, chose to deliberately ram the bomb.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 25 October 1942 over Guadalcanal, Marine First Lieutenant Jack E.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Conger of VMF-212 shot down three Mitsubishi A6M Zeroes.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Pursuing a fourth Zero, Conger ran out of ammunition and decided to use his propeller to chop the tail rudder off.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] However, Conger misjudged the distance between his plane and the Zero and struck the plane halfway between the cockpit and the tail, tearing the entire tail off.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Both Conger and the Zero pilot, Shiro Ishikawa, bailed out of their planes and were picked up by a rescue boat.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] For his actions, Conger was awarded the Navy Cross.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] During the battle of the Coral Sea, SBD pilot Stanley "Swede" Vejtasa was attacked by three A6M2 "Zero" fighters; he shot down two of them and cut off the wing of the third in a head-on pass with his wingtip.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 10 May 1945 over Okinawa, Marine First Lieutenant Robert R.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Klingman and three other pilots of VMF-312 climbed to intercept an aircraft they identified as a Kawasaki Ki-45 *Toryu* ("Nick") twin-engined heavy fighter flying reconnaissance at 25,000 feet (7,600 m), but the "Nick" began climbing higher.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Two of the FG-1D Corsairs ceased their pursuit at 36,000 feet (11,000 m), but Marine Captain Kenneth Reusser and his wingman Klingman continued to 38,000 feet (12,000 m), expending most of their .50 caliber ammunition to lighten their aircraft.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Reusser scored hits on the "Nick's" port engine, but ran out of ammunition, and was under fire from the Japanese rear gunner.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Klingman lined up for a shot at a distance of 50 feet (15 m) when his guns jammed due to the extreme cold.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] He approached the "Nick" three times to damage it with his propeller, chopping away at his opponent's rudder, rear cockpit, and right stabilizer.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The *Toryu* spun down to 15,000 feet (4,600 m) where its wings came off.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Despite missing five inches (13 cm) from the ends of his propeller blades, running out of fuel and having an aircraft dented and punctured by debris and bullets, Klingman safely guided his Corsair to a deadstick landing.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In the 1960 U-2 incident, Soviet pilot Igor Mentyukov was scrambled with orders to ram the intruding Lockheed U-2, using his unarmed Sukhoi Su-9 which had been modified for higher altitude flight.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In 1996, Mentyukov claimed that contact with his aircraft's slipstream downed Francis Gary Powers; however, Sergei Khrushchev asserted in 2000 that Mentyukov failed even to gain visual contact.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] On 7 September 1965, during the 1965 Indo-Pakistani War, a Pakistani Lockheed F-104A Starfighter (Serial No.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] 9 Squadron "Griffins" which was piloted by Flight Lieutenant Amjad Hussain Khan intercepted 6 Indian Mystere IVs which were attacking Sargodha Airbase.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] In the ensuing dogfight, a Mystere flown by Squadron Leader Devaiah forced Amjad's F-104 into low-speed dogfighting (something which the F-104 performs badly in due to its poor maneuverability at reduced speeds).
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Though Amjad scored several hits on Devaiah's Mystere with his M-61 Vulcan and even fired a GAR-8 at it (which missed), the Mystere was still flying.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Amjad ultimately made the first jet-to-jet ramming attack against the Indian warplane.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] This led to both pilots losing control of their aircraft over Kot Nakka.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] While the Indian pilot perished with his warplane, Amjad managed to eject safely and was rescued by Pakistani villagers watching the intense dogfight.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] Kulyapin reportedly used his Su-15 to ram a chartered Argentine CL-44 during the 1981 Armenia mid-air collision, although Western experts believed this likely to have been a self-serving interpretation of an accidental collision.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] A 1986 RAND Corporation study concluded that the ramming attack was still a viable option for modern jets defending their airspace from long-range bombers if those bombers were carrying atomic weapons.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The study posited that defending fighters might expend their weapons without downing the enemy bomber, and the pilots would then be faced with the final choice of ramming—almost certainly trading their lives for the many who would be killed by a successful nuclear attack.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] During the 9/11 attacks in 2001, fighter jets were dispatched to intercept the hijacked United Airlines Flight 93, believed to be heading to Washington.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] However, there was no time for the combat jets to be armed with missiles.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The pilots understood that they would be ramming the aircraft.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] The plane had already crashed due to an internal struggle by the time the jets arrived.
[src:battering-ram/aerial-ramming] During the Hainan island incident, an American EP-3 SIGINT aircraft was rammed by a PLANAF J-8 interceptor.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Born in Pella, Macedon, Alexander was tutored by philosopher and polymath Aristotle until the age of 16.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In 335 BC, shortly after assuming the throne of Macedon, he launched a campaign in the Balkans and reasserted control over Thrace and parts of Illyria before marching on the city of Thebes, which was subsequently destroyed.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then assumed leadership of the League of Corinth, created by his father.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] With this authority over all Greeks he launched a pan-Hellenic invasion of the Persian Achaemenid Empire in 334 BC, and with it began a series of campaigns which lasted for ten years.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Following his conquest of Asia Minor and a series of decisive battles, particularly at Issus and Gaugamela, the power of the Achaemenid Empire was broken.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He subsequently overthrew Darius III and conquered the Achaemenid Empire in its entirety.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After the fall of Persia, the Macedonian Empire held a vast swath of territory between the Adriatic Sea and the Indus River.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander endeavored to reach the "ends of the world and the Great Outer Sea" and invaded India in 326 BC, achieving an important victory over Porus, an ancient Indian king of present-day Punjab, at the Battle of the Hydaspes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Facing mutiny from troops, he was eventually forced to turn back at the Beas River, and later died in 323 BC in Babylon, Mesopotamia, the city which he had planned to make the capital of his empire, while on his return to Greece.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death put an end to his planned invasion of Arabia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the years following his death, a series of civil wars broke out across the Macedonian Empire, eventually leading to its disintegration at the hands of the Diadochi.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death marks the conventional beginning of the Hellenistic period.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Through his conquests, he built a legacy that includes the cultural diffusion and syncretism, which gave rise to Greco-Buddhism and Hellenistic Judaism.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He founded more than twenty cities, with the most prominent being the city of Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's establishment of Greek colonies and the spreading of Greek culture led to Hellenistic civilization becoming a major force in the ancient world, influencing regions as far east as the Indian subcontinent.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Hellenistic period developed through the Roman Empire into modern Western culture; the Greek language became the *lingua franca* of the region and was the predominant language of the Byzantine Empire until its collapse in 1453 AD.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander became a legendary hero similar to Achilles, featuring prominently in the historical and mythical traditions of both Greek and non-Greek cultures.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] His military achievements and successes in battle made him the touchstone against which many later military leaders would judge themselves.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] His tactics remain a significant subject of study in military academies worldwide.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Legends of Alexander's exploits were coalesced into the 3rd century *Alexander Romance* which, in the premodern period, went through over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations and was translated into almost every European vernacular and every language of the Islamic world.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After the Bible, it was the most popular form of European literature.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander III was born in Pella, the capital of the Kingdom of Macedon, on the sixth day of the ancient Greek month of Hekatombaion, which probably corresponds to 20 July 356 BC (although the exact date is uncertain).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He was the son of the king of Macedon, Philip II of the Argead dynasty and his fourth wife, Olympias (daughter of Neoptolemus I, Aeacid king of Epirus).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Although Philip had seven or eight wives, Olympias was his principal wife for some time, likely because she gave birth to Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Several legends surround Alexander's birth and childhood.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient Greek biographer Plutarch, on the eve of the consummation of her marriage to Philip, Olympias dreamed that her womb was struck by a thunderbolt that caused a flame to spread "far and wide" before dying away.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Sometime after the wedding, Philip is said to have seen himself, in a dream, securing his wife's womb with a seal engraved with a lion's image.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch offered a variety of interpretations for these dreams: that Olympias was pregnant before her marriage, indicated by the sealing of her womb; or that Alexander's father was Zeus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Ancient commentators were divided about whether the ambitious Olympias promulgated the story of Alexander's divine parentage, variously claiming that she had told Alexander, or that she dismissed the suggestion as impious.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] On the day Alexander was born, Philip was preparing a siege on the city of Potidea on the peninsula of Chalcidice.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] That same day, Philip received news that his general Parmenion had defeated the combined Illyrian and Paeonian armies and that his horses had won at the Olympic Games.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] It was also said that on this day, the Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, burnt down.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This led Hegesias of Magnesia to say that it had burnt down because Artemis was away, attending the birth of Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Such legends may have emerged when Alexander was king, and possibly at his instigation, to show that he was superhuman and destined for greatness from conception.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In his early years, Alexander was raised by a nurse, Lanike, sister of Alexander's future general Cleitus the Black.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Later in his childhood, Alexander was tutored by the strict Leonidas, a relative of his mother, and by Lysimachus of Acarnania.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was raised in the manner of noble Macedonian youths, learning to read, play the lyre, ride, fight, and hunt.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was ten years old, a trader from Thessaly brought Philip a horse, which he offered to sell for thirteen talents.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The horse refused to be mounted, and Philip ordered it away.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander, however, detecting the horse's fear of its own shadow, asked to tame the horse, which he eventually managed.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch stated that Philip, overjoyed at this display of courage and ambition, kissed his son tearfully, declaring: "My boy, you must find a kingdom big enough for your ambitions.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Macedon is too small for you", and bought the horse for him.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander named it Bucephalas, meaning "ox-head".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Bucephalas carried Alexander as far as modern day India.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Bucephalas died (because of old age, according to Plutarch, at age 30), Alexander named a city after him, Bucephala.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was 13, Philip began to search for a tutor, and considered such academics as Isocrates and Speusippus, the latter offering to resign from his stewardship of the Academy to take up the post.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the end, Philip chose Aristotle and provided the Temple of the Nymphs at Mieza as a classroom.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In return for teaching Alexander, Philip agreed to rebuild Aristotle's hometown of Stageira, which Philip had razed, and to repopulate it by buying and freeing the ex-citizens who were slaves, or pardoning those who were in exile.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Mieza was like a boarding school for Alexander and the children of Macedonian nobles, such as Ptolemy, Hephaestion, and Cassander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Many of these students would become his friends and future generals, and are often known as the "Companions".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander and his companions about medicine, philosophy, morals, religion, logic, and art.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Under Aristotle's tutelage, Alexander developed a passion for the works of Homer, and in particular the *Iliad*; Aristotle gave him an annotated copy, which Alexander later carried on his campaigns.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was able to quote Euripides from memory.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In his youth, Alexander was also acquainted with Persian exiles at the Macedonian court, who received the protection of Philip II for several years as they opposed Artaxerxes III.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Among them were Artabazos II and his daughter Barsine, possible future mistress of Alexander, who resided at the Macedonian court from 352 to 342 BC, as well as Amminapes, future satrap of Alexander, and a Persian nobleman named Sisines.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This gave the Macedonian court a good knowledge of Persian issues, and may even have influenced some of the innovations in the management of the Macedonian state.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Suda writes that Anaximenes of Lampsacus was one of Alexander's teachers, and that Anaximenes also accompanied Alexander on his campaigns.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] At the age of 16, Alexander's education under Aristotle ended.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip II had waged war against the Thracians to the north, which left Alexander in charge as regent and heir apparent.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During Philip's absence, the Thracian tribe of Maedi revolted against Macedonia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander responded quickly and drove them from their territory.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The territory was colonized, and a city, named Alexandropolis, was founded.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Upon Philip's return, Alexander was dispatched with a small force to subdue the revolts in southern Thrace.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Campaigning against the Greek city of Perinthus, Alexander reportedly saved his father's life.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, the city of Amphissa began to work lands that were sacred to Apollo near Delphi, a sacrilege that gave Philip the opportunity to further intervene in Greek affairs.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] While Philip was occupied in Thrace, Alexander was ordered to muster an army for a campaign in southern Greece.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Concerned that other Greek states might intervene, Alexander made it look as though he was preparing to attack Illyria instead.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During this turmoil, the Illyrians invaded Macedonia, only to be repelled by Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip and his army joined his son in 338 BC, and they marched south through Thermopylae, taking it after stubborn resistance from its Theban garrison.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] They went on to occupy the city of Elatea, only a few days' march from both Athens and Thebes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Athenians, led by Demosthenes, voted to seek alliance with Thebes against Macedonia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Both Athens and Philip sent embassies to win Thebes's favour, but Athens won the contest.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip marched on Amphissa (ostensibly acting on the request of the Amphictyonic League), capturing the mercenaries sent there by Demosthenes and accepting the city's surrender.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip then returned to Elatea, sending a final offer of peace to Athens and Thebes, who both rejected it.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As Philip marched south, his opponents blocked him near Chaeronea, Boeotia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During the ensuing Battle of Chaeronea, Philip commanded the right wing and Alexander the left, accompanied by a group of Philip's trusted generals.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient sources, the two sides fought bitterly for some time.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip deliberately commanded his troops to retreat, counting on the untested Athenian hoplites to follow, thus breaking their line.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was the first to break the Theban lines, followed by Philip's generals.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Having damaged the enemy's cohesion, Philip ordered his troops to press forward and quickly routed them.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] With the Athenians lost, the Thebans were surrounded.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Left to fight alone, they were defeated.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Following their victory at Chaeronea, Philip and Alexander marched unopposed into the Peloponnese, devastating much of Laconia and ejecting the Spartans from various parts of it.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] At Corinth, Philip established a "Hellenic Alliance" (modelled on the old anti-Persian alliance of the Greco-Persian Wars), which included most Greek city-states except Sparta.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip was then named *Hegemon* (often translated as "Supreme Commander") of this league (known by modern scholars as the League of Corinth), and announced his plans to attack the Persian Empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip returned to Pella, he fell in love with and married Cleopatra Eurydice in 338 BC, the niece of his general Attalus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The marriage made Alexander's position as heir less secure, since any son of Cleopatra Eurydice would be a fully Macedonian heir, while Alexander was only half-Macedonian.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During the wedding banquet, a drunken Attalus publicly prayed to the gods that the union would produce a legitimate heir.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] — Plutarch, describing the feud at Philip's wedding.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In 337 BC, Alexander fled Macedon with his mother, dropping her off with her brother, King Alexander I of Epirus in Dodona, capital of the Molossians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He continued to Illyria where he sought refuge with one or more Illyrian kings, perhaps with Glaucias, and was treated as a guest, despite having defeated them in battle a few years before.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] However, it appears Philip never intended to disown his politically and militarily trained son.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Accordingly, Alexander returned to Macedon after six months due to the efforts of a family friend, Demaratus, who mediated between the two parties.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, the Persian satrap (governor) of Caria, Pixodarus, offered his eldest daughter to Alexander's half-brother, Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias and several of Alexander's friends suggested this showed Philip intended to make Arrhidaeus his heir.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reacted by sending an actor, Thessalus of Corinth, to tell Pixodarus that he should not offer his daughter's hand to an illegitimate son, but instead to Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip heard of this, he stopped the negotiations and scolded Alexander for wishing to marry the daughter of a Carian, explaining that he wanted a better bride for him.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip exiled four of Alexander's friends, Harpalus, Nearchus, Ptolemy and Erigyius, and had the Corinthians bring Thessalus to him in chains.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As Pausanias tried to escape, he tripped over a vine and was killed by his pursuers, including two of Alexander's companions, Perdiccas and Leonnatus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was proclaimed king on the spot by the nobles and army at the age of 20.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander began his reign by eliminating potential rivals to the throne.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He had his cousin, the former Amyntas IV, executed and two Macedonian princes from the region of Lyncestis killed for having been involved in his father's assassination, but spared a third, Alexander Lyncestes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias had Cleopatra Eurydice, and Europa, her daughter by Philip, burned alive, though this infuriated Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander also ordered the murder of Cleopatra's uncle Attalus, who was in command of the advance guard of the army in Asia Minor.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Attalus was at that time corresponding with Demosthenes regarding the possibility of defecting to Athens, and had severely insulted Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After his niece's murder, Alexander may have considered him too dangerous to be left alive.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander spared Arrhidaeus, who was by all accounts mentally disabled, possibly as a result of poisoning by Olympias.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] News of Philip's death roused many states into revolt, including Thebes, Athens, Thessaly, and the Thracian tribes north of Macedon.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When news of the revolts reached Alexander, he responded quickly.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Though advised to use diplomacy, Alexander mustered 3,000 Macedonian cavalry and rode south towards Thessaly.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He found the Thessalian army occupying the pass between Mount Olympus and Mount Ossa, and ordered his men to ride over Mount Ossa.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When the Thessalians awoke the next day, they found Alexander in their rear and promptly surrendered, adding their cavalry to Alexander's force.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He then continued south towards the Peloponnese.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stopped at Thermopylae where he was recognized as the leader of the Amphictyonic League before heading south to Corinth.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Athens sued for peace and Alexander pardoned the rebels.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The famous encounter between Alexander and Diogenes the Cynic occurred during Alexander's stay in Corinth.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander asked Diogenes what he could do for him, the philosopher disdainfully asked Alexander to stand a little to the side, as he was blocking the sunlight.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This reply apparently delighted Alexander who is reported to have said, "But verily, if I were not Alexander, I would like to be Diogenes." At Corinth, Alexander took the title of *Hegemon* ("leader") and, like Philip, was appointed commander for the coming war against Persia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He also received news of a Thracian uprising.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Before crossing to Asia, Alexander wanted to safeguard his northern borders.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the spring of 335 BC, he advanced to suppress several revolts.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Starting from Amphipolis, he travelled east into the country of the "Independent Thracians", and at Mount Haemus, the Macedonian army attacked and defeated the Thracian forces manning the heights.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians marched into the country of the Triballi and defeated their army near the Lyginus river (a tributary of the Danube).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then marched for three days to the Danube, encountering the Getae tribe on the opposite shore.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Crossing the river at night, he surprised them and forced their army to retreat after the first cavalry skirmish.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] News then reached Alexander that the Illyrian chieftain Cleitus and King Glaukias of the Taulantii were in open revolt against his authority.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Marching west into Illyria, Alexander defeated each in turn, forcing the two rulers to flee with their troops.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] With these victories, he secured his northern frontier.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] While Alexander campaigned north, the Thebans and Athenians rebelled once again.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] While the other cities again hesitated, Thebes decided to fight.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Theban resistance was ineffective and Alexander razed the city and divided its territory between the other Boeotian cities.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The end of Thebes cowed Athens, leaving all of Greece temporarily at peace.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then set out on his Asian campaign, leaving Antipater as regent.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After securing his Greek base and the Balkans by subjugating his political opponents, and securing his army's rear through the conquest of all the Afro-Asian coastline, where the Persian fleet was based and from which it was supplied, Alexander moved to confront directly the Persians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In 336 he sent Parmenion, Amyntas, Andromenes, Attalus, and an army of 10,000 men into Anatolia to make preparations for an invasion.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greek cities on the western coast of Anatolia revolted until the news arrived that Philip had been murdered and had been succeeded by his young son Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians were demoralized by Philip's death and were subsequently defeated near Magnesia by the Achaemenids under the command of the mercenary Memnon of Rhodes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He showed his intent to conquer the entirety of the Persian Empire by throwing a spear into Asian soil and saying he accepted Asia as a gift from the gods.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This also showed Alexander's eagerness to fight, in contrast to his father's preference for diplomacy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After an initial victory against Persian forces at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander accepted the surrender of the Persian provincial capital and treasury of Sardis; he then proceeded along the Ionian coast, granting autonomy and democracy to the cities.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Miletus, held by Achaemenid forces, required a delicate siege operation, with Persian naval forces nearby.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Further south, at Halicarnassus, in Caria, Alexander successfully waged his first large-scale siege, eventually forcing his opponents, the mercenary captain Memnon of Rhodes and the Persian satrap of Caria, Orontobates, to withdraw by sea.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander left the government of Caria to a member of the Hecatomnid dynasty, Ada, who adopted Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] From Halicarnassus, Alexander proceeded into mountainous Lycia and the Pamphylian plain, asserting control over all coastal cities to deny the Persians naval bases.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] From Pamphylia onwards, the coast held no major ports and Alexander moved inland.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] At Termessos, Alexander humbled and did not storm the Pisidian city.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] At the ancient Phrygian capital of Gordium, Alexander "undid" the hitherto unsolvable Gordian Knot, a feat said to await the future "king of Asia".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the story, Alexander proclaimed that it did not matter how the knot was undone, and hacked it apart with his sword.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In spring 333 BC, Alexander crossed the Taurus into Cilicia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After a long pause due to an illness, he marched on towards Syria.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Though outmanoeuvered by Darius's significantly larger army, he marched back to Cilicia, where he defeated Darius at Issus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled the battle, causing his army to collapse, and left behind his wife, his two daughters, his mother Sisygambis, and a fabulous treasure.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He offered a peace treaty that included the lands he had lost, and a ransom of 10,000 talents for his family.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander replied that since he was now king of Asia, it was he alone who decided territorial divisions.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander proceeded to take possession of Syria, and most of the coast of the Levant.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, 332 BC, he was forced to attack Tyre, which he captured after a long and difficult siege.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The men of military age were massacred and the women and children sold into slavery.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander destroyed Tyre, most of the towns on the route to Egypt quickly capitulated.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander was met with resistance at Gaza.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The stronghold was heavily fortified and built on a hill, requiring a siege.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When "his engineers pointed out to him that because of the height of the mound it would be impossible... this encouraged Alexander all the more to make the attempt".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After three unsuccessful assaults, the stronghold fell, but not before Alexander had received a serious shoulder wound.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As in Tyre, men of military age were put to the sword, and the women and children were sold into slavery.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander advanced on Egypt in later 332 BC where he was regarded as a liberator.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] To legitimize taking power and be recognized as the descendant of the long line of pharaohs, Alexander made sacrifices to the gods at Memphis and went to consult the famous oracle of Amun-Ra at the Siwa Oasis in the Libyan desert, at which he was pronounced the son of the deity Amun.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Henceforth, Alexander often referred to Zeus-Ammon as his true father, and after his death, currency depicted him adorned with horns, using the Horns of Ammon as a symbol of his divinity.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks interpreted this message – one that the gods addressed to all pharaohs – as a prophecy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Egypt was only one of a large number of territories taken by Alexander from the Persians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After his trip to Siwa, Alexander was crowned in the temple of Ptah at Memphis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] It appears that the Egyptian people did not find it disturbing that he was a foreigner – nor that he was absent for virtually his entire reign.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander restored the temples neglected by the Persians and dedicated new monuments to the Egyptian gods.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the temple of Luxor, near Karnak, he built a chapel for the sacred barge.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During his brief months in Egypt, he reformed the taxation system on the Greek models and organized the military occupation of the country, but in early 331 BC he left for Asia in pursuit of the Persians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay in Egypt, he founded Alexandria, which would become the prosperous capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom after his death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Control of Egypt passed to Ptolemy I (son of Lagos), the founder of the Ptolemaic Dynasty (305–30 BC) after the death of Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Leaving Egypt in 331 BC, Alexander marched eastward into Achaemenid Assyria in Upper Mesopotamia (now northern Iraq) and defeated Darius again at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius once more fled the field, and Alexander chased him as far as Arbela.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Gaugamela would be the final and decisive encounter between the two.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled over the mountains to Ecbatana (modern Hamadan) while Alexander captured Babylon.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Babylonian astronomical diaries say that "the king of the world, Alexander" sent his scouts with a message to the people of Babylon before entering the city: "I shall not enter your houses".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] From Babylon, Alexander went to Susa, one of the Achaemenid capitals, and captured its treasury.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He sent the bulk of his army to the Persian ceremonial capital of Persepolis via the Persian Royal Road.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander himself took selected troops on the direct route to the city.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He then stormed the pass of the Persian Gates (in the modern Zagros Mountains) which had been blocked by a Persian army under Ariobarzanes and then hurried to Persepolis before its garrison could loot the treasury.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] On entering Persepolis, Alexander allowed his troops to loot the city for several days.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stayed in Persepolis for five months.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay, a fire broke out in the eastern palace of Xerxes I and spread to the rest of the city.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Possible causes include a drunken accident or deliberate revenge for the burning of the Acropolis of Athens during the Second Persian War by Xerxes; Plutarch and Diodorus allege that Alexander's companion, the hetaera Thaïs, instigated and started the fire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Even as he watched the city burn, Alexander immediately began to regret his decision.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch claims that he ordered his men to put out the fires but the flames had already spread to most of the city.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Curtius claims that Alexander did not regret his decision until the next morning.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then chased Darius, first into Media, and then Parthia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Persian king no longer controlled his own destiny, and was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men fatally stab the Great King and then declared himself Darius's successor as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia to launch a guerrilla campaign against Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander buried Darius's remains next to his Achaemenid predecessors in a regal funeral.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He claimed that, while dying, Darius had named him as his successor to the Achaemenid throne.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is normally considered to have fallen with Darius.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander viewed Bessus as an usurper and set out to defeat him.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This campaign, initially against Bessus, turned into a grand tour of central Asia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded a series of new cities, all called Alexandria, including modern Kandahar in Afghanistan, and Alexandria Eschate ("The Furthest") in modern Tajikistan.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The campaign took Alexander through a number of satrapies in present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia, including Media, Parthia, Aria, Drangiana, Arachosia, Bactria, and Scythia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In 329 BC, Spitamenes, who held an undefined position in the satrapy of Sogdiana, betrayed Bessus to Ptolemy, one of Alexander's trusted companions, and Bessus was executed.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] However, at some point later when Alexander was on the Jaxartes dealing with an incursion by a horse nomad army, Spitamenes raised Sogdiana in revolt.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander personally defeated the Scythians at the Battle of Jaxartes and immediately launched a campaign against Spitamenes, defeating him in the Battle of Gabai.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After the defeat, Spitamenes was killed by his own men, who then sued for peace.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During this time, Alexander adopted some elements of Persian dress and customs at his court, notably the custom of *proskynesis*, either a symbolic kissing of the hand, or prostration on the ground, that Persians showed to their social superiors.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This was one aspect of Alexander's broad strategy aimed at securing the aid and support of the Iranian upper classes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks however regarded the gesture of *proskynesis* as the province of deities and believed that Alexander meant to deify himself by requiring it.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen, and he eventually abandoned it.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During the long rule of the Achaemenids, the elite positions in many segments of the empire including the central government, the army, and the many satrapies were specifically reserved for Iranians and to a major degree, Persian noblemen.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The latter were in many cases additionally connected through marriage alliances with the royal Achaemenid family.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This created a problem for Alexander as to whether he had to make use of the various segments and people that had given the empire its solidity and unity for a lengthy period of time.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Pierre Briant explains that Alexander realized that it was insufficient to merely exploit the internal contradictions within the imperial system as in Asia Minor, Babylonia or Egypt; he also had to (re)create a central government with or without the support of the Iranians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As early as 334 BC he demonstrated awareness of this, when he challenged incumbent King Darius III "by appropriating the main elements of the Achaemenid monarchy's ideology, particularly the theme of the king who protects the lands and the peasants".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander wrote a letter in 332 BC to Darius III, wherein he argued that he was worthier than Darius "to succeed to the Achaemenid throne".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's eventual decision to burn the Achaemenid palace at Persepolis in conjunction with the major rejection and opposition of the "entire Persian people" made it impracticable for him to pose himself as Darius' legitimate successor.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Against Bessus (Artaxerxes V) however, Briant adds, Alexander reasserted "his claim to legitimacy as the avenger of Darius III".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] A plot against his life was revealed, and one of his officers, Philotas, was executed for failing to alert Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The death of the son necessitated the death of the father, and thus Parmenion, who had been charged with guarding the treasury at Ecbatana, was assassinated at Alexander's command, to prevent attempts at vengeance.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Later, in the Central Asian campaign, a second plot against his life was revealed.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This one was instigated by his own royal pages.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] His official historian, Callisthenes of Olynthus, was implicated in the plot, and in the *Anabasis of Alexander*, Arrian states that Callisthenes and the pages were then tortured on the rack as punishment, and likely died soon after.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] It remains unclear if Callisthenes was actually involved in the plot, for prior to his accusation he had fallen out of favour by leading the opposition to the attempt to introduce proskynesis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander set out for Asia, he left his general Antipater, an experienced military and political leader, and part of Philip II's "Old Guard", in charge of Macedon.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's sacking of Thebes ensured that Greece remained quiet during his absence.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The one exception was a call to arms by Spartan king Agis III in 331 BC, whom Antipater defeated and killed in the battle of Megalopolis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Antipater referred the Spartans' punishment to the League of Corinth, which then deferred to Alexander, who chose to pardon them.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] There was also considerable friction between Antipater and Olympias, and each complained to Alexander about the other.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In general, Greece enjoyed a period of peace and prosperity during Alexander's campaign in Asia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent back vast sums from his conquest, which stimulated the economy and increased trade across his empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's constant demands for troops and the migration of Macedonians throughout his empire depleted Macedon's strength, greatly weakening it in the years after Alexander, and ultimately led to its subjugation by Rome after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BC).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The conquest by Philip II of Pangaeum, and then of the island of Thasos between 356 and 342 BC brought rich gold and silver mines under Macedonian control.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander appears to have introduced a new coinage in Cilicia in Tarsus, after the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, which went on to become the main coinage of the empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander minted gold staters, silver tetradrachms and drachims, and various fractional bronze coins.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The types of these coins remained constant in his empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The gold series had the head of Athena on the obverse and a winged Nike (Victory) on the reverse.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The silver coinage had a beardless head of Heracles wearing a lionskin headdress on the obverse and Zeus aetophoros ('eagle bearer') enthroned with a scepter in his left hand, on the reverse.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] There are both Greek and non-Greek aspects to this design.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Heracles and Zeus were important deities for the Macedonians, with Heracles considered to be the ancestor of the Temenid dynasty and Zeus the patron of the main Macedonian sanctuary, Dium.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The lion was also the symbolic animal of the Anatolian god Sandas, worshipped at Tarsus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The reverse design of Alexander's tetradrachms is closely modelled on the depiction of the god Baaltars (Baal of Tarsus), on the silver staters minted at Tarsus by the Persian satrap Mazaeus before Alexander's conquest.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander did not attempt to impose uniform imperial coinage throughout his new conquests.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Persian coins continued to circulate in all the satrapies of the empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Spitamenes and his marriage to Roxana (Raoxshna in Old Iranian) to cement relations with his new satrapies, Alexander turned to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He invited the chieftains of the former satrapy of Gandhara (in the present-day Peshawar Valley), to come to him and submit to his authority.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the winter of 327/326 BC, Alexander personally led Cophen campaign against the Aspasioi of the Kunar Valley, the Guraeans of the Panjkora Valley, and the Assakenoi of the Swat Valley.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] A fierce contest ensued with the Aspasioi in which Alexander was wounded in the shoulder by a dart, but eventually the Aspasioi lost.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then faced the Assakenoi who fought against him from the strongholds of Massaga, Ora, and Aornos.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The fort of Massaga was reduced after days of bloody fighting in which Alexander was seriously wounded in the ankle.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] According to Curtius, "Not only did Alexander slaughter the entire population of Massaga, but also did he reduce its buildings to rubble." A similar massacre followed at Ora.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In the aftermath of Massaga and Ora, numerous Assakenians fled to the fortress of Aornos.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander followed close behind and captured the strategic hill-fort after four bloody days.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Assakenoi leader, his mother queen Cleophis submitted to Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After Aornos, Alexander crossed the Indus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis hastened to relieve Alexander of his apprehension and met him with valuable presents, placing himself and all his forces at his disposal.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander not only returned Omphis his title and the gifts but he also presented him with a wardrobe of "Persian robes, gold and silver ornaments, 30 horses and 1,000 talents in gold".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] On the subsequent advance of the Macedonian king, Omphis accompanied him with a force of 5,000 men and took part in the Battle of the Hydaspes against the King Porus, who ruled territory lying between the Hydaspes and the Acesines (Chenab) in the Punjab, in 326 BC.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander won an epic battle against Porus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis was sent by Alexander in pursuit of Porus, to whom he was charged to offer favourable terms, but narrowly escaped losing his life at the hands of his old enemy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Subsequently, the two rivals were reconciled by the personal mediation of Alexander; Omphis contributed zealously to the equipment of the fleet on the Hydaspes and was entrusted by Alexander with the government of the whole territory between that river and the Indus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was also impressed by Porus's bravery and made him an ally.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] He appointed Porus as satrap, and added to Porus's territory land that he did not previously own, towards the south-east, up to the Hyphasis (Beas).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Choosing local rulers helped him control these lands that were distant from Greece.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] A considerable accession of power was granted him after the death of Philip, son of Machatas, and he was allowed to retain his authority at the death of Alexander himself (323 BC), as well as in the subsequent partition of the provinces at Triparadisus, 321 BC.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded two cities on opposite sides of the Hydaspes river, naming one Bucephala, in honour of his horse, who died around this time.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The other was Nicaea (Victory), believed to be located at the site of modern-day Mong.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Philostratus the Elder in the *Life of Apollonius of Tyana* writes that in the army of Porus, there was an elephant who fought bravely against Alexander's army, and Alexander dedicated it to the Helios (Sun) and named it Ajax because he thought that such a great animal deserved a great name.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The elephant had gold rings around its tusks and an inscription was on them written in Greek: "Alexander the son of Zeus dedicates Ajax to the Helios" (ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΣ Ο ΔΙΟΣ ΤΟΝ ΑΙΑΝΤΑ ΤΩΙ ΗΛΙΩΙ).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] East of Porus's kingdom, near the Ganges River, was the Nanda Empire of Magadha, and further east, the Gangaridai Empire of Bengal region.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Fearing the prospect of facing other large armies and exhausted by years of campaigning, Alexander's army mutinied at the Hyphasis River (Beas), refusing to march farther east.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] This river thus marks the easternmost extent of Alexander's conquests.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander tried to persuade his soldiers to march farther, but his general Coenus pleaded with him to change his opinion and return; the men, he said, "longed to again see their parents, their wives and children, their homeland".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander eventually agreed and turned south, marching along the Indus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Along the way his army conquered the territory inhabited by the Mallians in the Mallian campaign; while besieging the Mallian citadel, Alexander suffered a near-fatal injury when an arrow penetrated his armor and entered his lung.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent much of his army to Carmania (modern southern Iran) with general Craterus, and commissioned a fleet to explore the Persian Gulf shore under his admiral Nearchus, while he led the rest back to Persia through the more difficult southern route along the Gedrosian Desert and Makran.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reached Susa in 324 BC, but not before losing many men to the harsh desert.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Discovering that many of his satraps and military governors had misbehaved in his absence, Alexander executed several of them as examples on his way to Susa.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] As a gesture of thanks, he paid off the debts of his soldiers, and announced he would send over-aged and disabled veterans back to Macedon, led by Craterus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] His troops misunderstood his intention and mutinied at the town of Opis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] They refused to be sent away and criticized his adoption of Persian customs and dress and the introduction of Persian officers and soldiers into Macedonian units.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] After three days, unable to persuade his men to back down, Alexander gave Persians command posts in the army and conferred Macedonian military titles upon Persian units.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians quickly begged forgiveness, which Alexander accepted, and held a great banquet with several thousand of his men.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] In an attempt to craft a lasting harmony between his Macedonian and Persian subjects, Alexander held a mass marriage of his senior officers to Persian and other noblewomen at Susa, but few of those marriages seem to have lasted much beyond a year.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, upon his return to Persia, Alexander learned that guards of the tomb of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae had desecrated it, and swiftly executed them.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander admired Cyrus the Great, from an early age reading Xenophon's *Cyropaedia*, which described Cyrus's heroism in battle and governance as a king and legislator.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] During his visit to Pasargadae, Alexander ordered his architect Aristobulus to decorate the interior of the sepulchral chamber of Cyrus's tomb.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Afterwards, Alexander travelled to Ecbatana to retrieve the bulk of the Persian treasure.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] There, his closest friend, Hephaestion, died of illness or poisoning.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander and he ordered the preparation of an expensive funeral pyre in Babylon along with a decree for public mourning.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p01] Back in Babylon, Alexander planned a series of new campaigns, beginning with an invasion of Arabia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] On either 10 or 11 June 323 BC, Alexander died in the palace of Nebuchadnezzar II, in Babylon, at age 32.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] There are two different versions of Alexander's death, differing slightly in details.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Plutarch's account is that roughly 14 days before his death, Alexander entertained admiral Nearchus and spent the night and next day drinking with Medius of Larissa.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander developed a fever, which worsened until he was unable to speak.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The common soldiers, anxious about his health, were granted the right to file past him as he silently waved at them.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In the second account, Diodorus recounts that Alexander was struck with pain after downing a large bowl of unmixed wine in honour of Heracles followed by 11 days of weakness; he did not develop a fever, instead dying after some agony.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian also mentioned this as an alternative, but Plutarch specifically denied this claim.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Given the propensity of the Macedonian aristocracy to assassination and Alexander's relatively young age, foul play featured in multiple accounts of his death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Plutarch, Arrian and Justin all mentioned the theory that Alexander was poisoned.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Justin stated that Alexander was the victim of a poisoning conspiracy, Plutarch dismissed it as a fabrication, while both Diodorus and Arrian noted that they mentioned it only for the sake of completeness.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The accounts were nevertheless fairly consistent in designating Antipater, recently removed as Macedonian viceroy, replaced by Craterus, as the head of the alleged plot.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps taking his summons to Babylon as a death sentence and having seen the fate of Parmenion and Philotas, Antipater purportedly arranged for Alexander to be poisoned by his son Iollas, who was Alexander's wine-pourer.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] There was even a suggestion that Aristotle may have participated.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The strongest argument against the poison theory is the fact that twelve days passed between the start of his illness and his death; such long-acting poisons were probably not available.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in a 2003 BBC documentary investigating the death of Alexander, Leo Schep from the New Zealand National Poisons Centre proposed that the plant white hellebore (*Veratrum album*), which was known in antiquity, may have been used to poison Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In a 2014 manuscript in the journal *Clinical Toxicology*, Schep suggested Alexander's wine was spiked with *Veratrum album*, and that this would produce poisoning symptoms that match the course of events described in the *Alexander Romance*.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] *Veratrum album* poisoning can have a prolonged course and it was suggested that if Alexander was poisoned, *Veratrum album* offers the most plausible cause.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Another poisoning explanation put forward in 2010 proposed that the circumstances of his death were compatible with poisoning by water of the river Styx (modern-day Mavroneri in Arcadia, Greece) that contained calicheamicin, a dangerous compound produced by bacteria.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Several natural causes (diseases) have been suggested, including malaria and typhoid fever.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] A 1998 article in the *New England Journal of Medicine* attributed his death to typhoid fever complicated by bowel perforation and ascending paralysis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] A 2004 analysis suggested pyogenic (infectious) spondylitis or meningitis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Other illnesses fit the symptoms, including acute pancreatitis, West Nile virus, and Guillain-Barré syndrome.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Natural-cause theories also tend to emphasize that Alexander's health may have been in general decline after years of heavy drinking and severe wounds.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The anguish that Alexander felt after Hephaestion's death may also have contributed to his declining health.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's body was laid in a gold anthropoid sarcophagus that was filled with honey, which was in turn placed in a gold casket.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Aelian, a seer called Aristander foretold that the land where Alexander was laid to rest "would be happy and unvanquishable forever".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps more likely, the successors may have seen possession of the body as a symbol of legitimacy, since burying the prior king was a royal prerogative.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander's funeral cortege was on its way to Macedon, Ptolemy seized it and took it temporarily to Memphis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His successor, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, transferred the sarcophagus to Alexandria, where it remained until at least late antiquity.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Ptolemy IX Lathyros, one of Ptolemy's final successors, replaced Alexander's sarcophagus with a glass one so he could convert the original to coinage.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The 2014 discovery of an enormous tomb in northern Greece, at Amphipolis, dating from the time of Alexander the Great has given rise to speculation that its original intent was to be the burial place of Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This would fit with the intended destination of Alexander's funeral cortege.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the memorial was found to be dedicated to the dearest friend of Alexander the Great, Hephaestion.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey, Julius Caesar and Augustus all visited the tomb in Alexandria where Augustus, allegedly, accidentally knocked the nose of Alexander's mummified body off.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula was said to have taken Alexander's breastplate from the tomb for his own use.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Around AD 200, Emperor Septimius Severus closed Alexander's tomb to the public.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His son and successor, Caracalla, a great admirer, visited the tomb during his own reign.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] After this, details on the fate of the tomb are hazy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The so-called "Alexander Sarcophagus", discovered near Sidon and now in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum, is so named not because it was thought to have contained Alexander's remains, but because its bas-reliefs depict Alexander and his companions fighting the Persians and hunting.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] It was originally thought to have been the sarcophagus of Abdalonymus (died 311 BC), the king of Sidon appointed by Alexander immediately following the Battle of Issus in 332.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1969, it was suggested by Karl Schefold that it may date from earlier than Abdalonymus's death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Demades likened the Macedonian army, after the death of Alexander, to the blinded Cyclops due to the many random and disorderly movements that it made.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In addition, Leosthenes also likened the anarchy between the generals, after Alexander's death, to the blinded Cyclops "who after he had lost his eye went feeling and groping about with his hands before him, not knowing where to lay them".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's death was so sudden that when reports of his death reached Greece, they were not immediately believed.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander had no obvious or legitimate heir, his son Alexander IV by Roxane being born after Alexander's death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's companions asked him on his deathbed to whom he bequeathed his kingdom; his laconic reply was "tôi kratistôi"—"to the strongest".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Another theory is that his successors wilfully or erroneously misheard "tôi Kraterôi"—"to Craterus", the general leading his Macedonian troops home and newly entrusted with the regency of Macedonia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian and Plutarch claimed that Alexander was speechless by this time, implying that this was an apocryphal story.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Curtius and Justin offered the more plausible story that Alexander passed his signet ring to Perdiccas, a bodyguard and leader of the companion cavalry, in front of witnesses, thereby nominating him.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Perdiccas initially did not claim power, instead suggesting that Roxane's baby would be king, if male, with himself, Craterus, Leonnatus, and Antipater as guardians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the infantry, under the command of Meleager, rejected this arrangement since they had been excluded from the discussion.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Instead, they supported Alexander's half-brother Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Eventually, the two sides reconciled, and after the birth of Alexander IV, he and Philip III were appointed joint kings, albeit in name only.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Dissension and rivalry soon affected the Macedonians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The satrapies handed out by Perdiccas at the Partition of Babylon became power bases each general used to bid for power.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] After the assassination of Perdiccas in 321 BC, Macedonian unity collapsed, and 40 years of war between "The Successors" (*Diadochi*) ensued before the Hellenistic world settled into three stable power blocs: Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Syria and Persia, and Antigonid Macedonia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In the process, both Alexander IV and Philip III were murdered.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus stated that Alexander had given detailed written instructions to Craterus some time before his death, which are known as Alexander's "last plans".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Craterus started to carry out Alexander's commands, but the successors chose not to further implement them, on the grounds they were impractical and extravagant.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, Perdiccas had read the notebooks containing Alexander's last plans to the Macedonian troops in Babylon, who voted not to carry them out.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's last plans called for military expansion into the southern and western Mediterranean, monumental constructions, and the intermixing of Eastern and Western populations.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The enormous scale of these plans has led many scholars to doubt their historicity.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Ernst Badian argued that they were exaggerated by Perdiccas in order to ensure that the Macedonian troops voted not to carry them out.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Other scholars have proposed that they were invented by later authors within the tradition of the Alexander Romance.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander perhaps earned the epithet "the Great" due to his unparalleled success as a military commander; he never lost a battle, despite typically being outnumbered.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This was due to use of terrain, phalanx and cavalry tactics, bold strategy, and the fierce loyalty of his troops.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macedonian phalanx, armed with the sarissa, a spear 6 metres (20 ft) long, had been developed and perfected by Philip II through rigorous training, and Alexander used its speed and manoeuvrability to great effect against larger but more disparate Persian forces.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also recognized the potential for disunity among his diverse army, which employed various languages and weapons.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He overcame this by being personally involved in battle, in the manner of a Macedonian king.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In his first battle in Asia, at Granicus, Alexander used only a small part of his forces, perhaps 13,000 infantry with 5,000 cavalry, against a much larger Persian force of 40,000.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander placed the phalanx at the center and cavalry and archers on the wings, so that his line matched the length of the Persian cavalry line, about 3 km (1.86 mi).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] By contrast, the Persian infantry was stationed behind its cavalry.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This ensured that Alexander would not be outflanked, while his phalanx, armed with long pikes, had a considerable advantage over the Persians' scimitars and javelins.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Macedonian losses were negligible compared to those of the Persians.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] At Issus in 333 BC, his first confrontation with Darius, he used the same deployment, and again the central phalanx pushed through.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander personally led the charge in the center, routing the opposing army.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] At the decisive encounter with Darius at Gaugamela, Darius equipped his chariots with scythes on the wheels to break up the phalanx and equipped his cavalry with pikes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander arranged a double phalanx, with the center advancing at an angle, parting when the chariots bore down and then reforming.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The advance was successful and broke Darius's center, causing the latter to flee once again.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] When faced with opponents who used unfamiliar fighting techniques, such as in Central Asia and India, Alexander adapted his forces to his opponents' style.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, in Bactria and Sogdiana, Alexander successfully used his javelin throwers and archers to prevent outflanking movements, while massing his cavalry at the center.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In India, confronted by Porus's elephant corps, the Macedonians opened their ranks to envelop the elephants and used their sarissas to strike upwards and dislodge the elephants' handlers.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Historical sources frequently give conflicting accounts of Alexander's appearance, and the earliest sources are the most scant in their detail; for example, Arrian describes him simply as "very handsome".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] During his lifetime, Alexander carefully curated his image by commissioning works from famous and great artists of the time.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This included commissioning sculptures by Lysippos, paintings by Apelles and gem engravings by Pyrgoteles.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Ancient authors recorded that Alexander was so pleased with portraits of himself created by Lysippos that he forbade other sculptors from crafting his image; scholars today, however, find the claim dubious.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, though idealised, Lysippos's sculpture was thought to be the most faithful plastic representation.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] 3rd century BC bust of Alexander from Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Both Curtius and Diodorus report a story that when Darius III's mother, Sisygambis, first met Alexander and Hephaestion, she assumed that the latter was Alexander because he was the taller and more physically impressive of the two.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Historians have understood the detail of the pleasant fragrance attributed to Alexander as stemming from a belief in ancient Greece that pleasant scents are characteristic of gods and heroes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Alexander Mosaic and contemporary coins portray Alexander with "a straight nose, a slightly protruding jaw, full lips and eyes deep set beneath a strongly pronounced forehead".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He is also described as having a slight upward tilt of his head to the left.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] 235 AD), in his *Varia Historia* (12.14), describes Alexander's hair color as "ξανθὴν" (*xanthen*), which at the time, could mean blond, brown, tawny (light brown) or auburn.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] It is sometimes claimed that Alexander had one blue and one brown eye, referring to the *Alexander Romance*, which is however a fictional account that also claims Alexander "had sharp teeth like fangs" and "did not look like Philip or Olympias".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Reconstruction, based on remaining traces of paint of the original polychromy on the Alexander Sarcophagus from Sidon, indicates that he was depicted with brown eyes and chestnut brown hair.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Acropolis Museum suggests that trace amounts of red paint on a head statue of Alexander found in 1886 were most likely a base coat for golden hues to be painted over for his hair.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Pella mosaic of a lion hunt (late 4th century BC) depicts him as having blond hair, with empty spots where their eye stones (which would've been used with semi-precious gems) having been plucked out.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Both of Alexander's parents encouraged his ambitions.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His father Philip was probably Alexander's most immediate and influential role model, as the young Alexander watched him campaign practically every year, winning victory after victory while ignoring severe wounds.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's relationship with his father "forged" the competitive side of his personality; he had a need to outdo his father, illustrated by his reckless behavior in battle.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander worried that his father would leave him "no great or brilliant achievement to be displayed to the world", he also downplayed his father's achievements to his companions.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's mother Olympias similarly had huge ambitions, and encouraged her son to believe it was his destiny to conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] She instilled a sense of destiny in him, and Plutarch tells how his ambition "kept his spirit serious and lofty in advance of his years".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Plutarch, Alexander also had a violent temper and rash, impulsive nature, which could influence his decision making.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Although Alexander was stubborn and did not respond well to orders from his father, he was open to reasoned debate.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a calmer side—perceptive, logical, and calculating.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a great desire for knowledge, a love for philosophy, and was an avid reader.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This was no doubt in part due to Aristotle's tutelage; Alexander was intelligent and quick to learn.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His intelligent and rational side was amply demonstrated by his ability and success as a general.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great self-restraint in "pleasures of the body", in contrast with his lack of self-control with alcohol.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was erudite and patronized both arts and sciences.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, he had little interest in sports or the Olympic Games (unlike his father), seeking only the Homeric ideals of honour (*timê*) and glory (*kudos*).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great charisma and force of personality, characteristics which made him a great leader.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His unique abilities were further demonstrated by the inability of any of his generals to unite Macedonia and retain the Empire after his death—only Alexander had the ability to do so.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] During his final years, and especially after the death of Hephaestion, Alexander began to exhibit signs of megalomania and paranoia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His extraordinary achievements, coupled with his own ineffable sense of destiny and the flattery of his companions, may have combined to produce this effect.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His delusions of grandeur are readily visible in his will and in his desire to conquer the world, in as much as he is by various sources described as having *boundless ambition*, an epithet, the meaning of which has descended into a historical cliché.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He appears to have believed himself a deity, or at least sought to deify himself.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Olympias always insisted to him that he was the son of Zeus, an idea apparently confirmed to him by the oracle of Amun at Siwa.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He began to identify himself as the son of Zeus-Ammon.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This behaviour cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also was a pragmatic ruler who understood the difficulties of ruling culturally disparate peoples, many of whom lived in societies where the king was treated as divine.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, rather than megalomania, his behaviour may have been a practical attempt at strengthening his rule and keeping his empire together.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander married three times: Roxana, daughter of the Sogdian nobleman Oxyartes of Bactria, out of love; the Persian princesses Stateira and Parysatis, the former a daughter of Darius III and the latter a daughter of Artaxerxes III, for political reasons.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander apparently had two children by Roxana: a son, who was born in India and died in infancy in November 326 BC, and Alexander IV of Macedon, born after his father's death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Additionally Heracles of Macedon was claimed to be his illegitimate son born of mistress, Barsine.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also had a close relationship with his friend, general, and bodyguard Hephaestion, the son of a Macedonian noble.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This event may have contributed to Alexander's failing health and detached mental state during his final months.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's sexuality has been the subject of speculation and controversy in modern times.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Roman era writer Athenaeus says, based on the scholar Dicaearchus, who was Alexander's contemporary, that the king "was quite excessively keen on boys", and that Alexander kissed the eunuch Bagoas in public.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This episode is also told by Plutarch, probably based on the same source.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Historian William Woodthorpe Tarn rejected the stories of Bagoas as fabricated in ancient times to defame Alexander, mainly referring to the Rufus's fairly fictionalized biography of Alexander that criticized the Macedonian's "degeneration" in embracing foreign Persian customs.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1958 Badian countered Tarn's arguments, though his concern was the issue of the reliability of sources for Alexander rather than the figure of the eunuch himself.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] None of Alexander's contemporaries, however, are known to have explicitly described Alexander's relationship with Hephaestion as sexual, though the pair was often compared to Achilles and Patroclus, who are often interpreted as a couple.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Some modern historians (e.g., Robin Lane Fox) believe not only that Alexander's youthful relationship with Hephaestion was sexual, but also that their sexual contacts may have continued into adulthood, which went against the social norms of at least some Greek cities, such as Athens.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, some modern researchers have tentatively proposed that Macedonia (or at least the Macedonian court) may have been more tolerant of homosexuality between adults.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Peter Green argues that there is little evidence in ancient sources that Alexander had much sexual interest in women; he did not produce an heir until the very end of his life.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, Ogden calculates that Alexander, who impregnated his partners three times in eight years, had fathered more children than his father at the same age.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Two of these pregnancies—Stateira's and Barsine's—are of dubious legitimacy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus Siculus, Alexander accumulated a harem in the style of Persian kings, but he used it rather sparingly, "not wishing to offend the Macedonians", showing great self-control in "pleasures of the body".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, Plutarch described how Alexander was infatuated by Roxana while complimenting him on not forcing himself on her.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Green suggested that, in the context of the period, Alexander formed quite strong friendships with women, including Ada of Caria, who adopted him, and even Darius's mother Sisygambis, who supposedly died from grief upon hearing of Alexander's death.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's legacy extended beyond his military conquests, and his reign marked a turning point in European and Asian history.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His campaigns greatly increased contacts and trade between East and West, and vast areas to the east were significantly exposed to Greek civilization and influence.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the cities he founded became major cultural centers, many surviving into the 21st century.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His chroniclers recorded valuable information about the areas through which he marched, while the Greeks themselves got a sense of belonging to a world beyond the Mediterranean.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's most immediate legacy was the introduction of Macedonian rule to huge new swathes of Asia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] At the time of his death, Alexander's empire covered some 5,200,000 km2 (2,000,000 sq mi), and was the largest state of its time.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of these areas remained in Macedonian hands or under Greek influence for the next 200–300 years.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The successor states that emerged were, at least initially, dominant forces, and these 300 years are often referred to as the Hellenistic period.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The eastern borders of Alexander's empire began to collapse even during his lifetime.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the power vacuum he left in the northwest of the Indian subcontinent directly gave rise to one of the most powerful Indian dynasties in history, the Maurya Empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Taking advantage of this power vacuum, Chandragupta Maurya (referred to in Greek sources as "Sandrokottos"), of relatively humble origin, took control of the Punjab, and with that power base proceeded to conquer the Nanda Empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Over the course of his conquests, Alexander founded many cities that bore his name, most of them east of the Tigris.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The first, and greatest, was Alexandria in Egypt, which would become one of the leading Mediterranean cities.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The cities' locations reflected trade routes as well as defensive positions.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] At first, the cities must have been inhospitable, little more than defensive garrisons.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Following Alexander's death, many Greeks who had settled there tried to return to Greece.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] However, a century or so after Alexander's death, many of the Alexandrias were thriving, with elaborate public buildings and substantial populations that included both Greek and local peoples.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In 334 BC, Alexander the Great donated funds for the completion of the new temple of Athena Polias in Priene, in modern-day western Turkey.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] An inscription from the temple, now housed in the British Museum, declares: "King Alexander dedicated [this temple] to Athena Polias." This inscription is one of the few independent archaeological discoveries confirming an episode from Alexander's life.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The temple was designed by Pytheos, one of the architects of the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Libanius wrote that Alexander founded the temple of Zeus Bottiaios (Ancient Greek: Βοττιαίου Δῖός), in the place where later the city of Antioch was built.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Suda wrote that Alexander built a big temple to Sarapis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In 2023, British Museum experts have suggested the possibility that a Greek temple at Girsu in Iraq, was founded by Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to the researchers, recent discoveries suggest that "this site honours Zeus and two divine sons.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The term *Hellenization* was coined by the German historian Johann Gustav Droysen to denote the spread of Greek language, culture, and population into the former Persian empire after Alexander's conquest.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This process can be seen in such great Hellenistic cities as Alexandria, Antioch and Seleucia (south of modern Baghdad).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander sought to insert Greek elements into Persian culture and to hybridize Greek and Persian culture, homogenizing the populations of Asia and Europe.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Although his successors explicitly rejected such policies, Hellenization occurred throughout the region, accompanied by a distinct and opposite 'Orientalization' of the successor states.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The core of the Hellenistic culture promulgated by the conquests was essentially Athenian.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The close association of men from across Greece in Alexander's army directly led to the emergence of the largely Attic-based "koine", or "common" Greek dialect.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Koine spread throughout the Hellenistic world, becoming the lingua franca of Hellenistic lands, and eventually the ancestor of modern Greek.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, town planning, education, local government, and art current in the Hellenistic period were all based on Classical Greek ideals, evolving into distinct new forms commonly grouped as Hellenistic.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Also, the New Testament was written in the Koine Greek language.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Aspects of Hellenistic culture were still evident in the traditions of the Byzantine Empire in the mid-15th century.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the most pronounced effects of Hellenization can be seen in Afghanistan and India, in the region of the relatively late-rising Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (250–125 BC) (in modern Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Tajikistan) and the Indo-Greek Kingdom (180 BC – 10 AD) in modern Afghanistan and India.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] On the Silk Road trade routes, Hellenistic culture hybridized with Iranian and Buddhist cultures.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The resulting syncretism known as Greco-Buddhism influenced the development of Buddhism and created a culture of Greco-Buddhist art.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] These Greco-Buddhist kingdoms sent some of the first Buddhist missionaries to China, Sri Lanka and Hellenistic Asia and Europe (Greco-Buddhist monasticism).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the first and most influential figurative portrayals of The Buddha appeared at this time, perhaps modelled on Greek statues of Apollo in the Greco-Buddhist style.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] One Greek king, Menander I, probably became Buddhist, and was immortalized in Buddhist literature as 'Milinda'.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The process of Hellenization also spurred trade between the east and west.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] 'Greek astronomical treatise') and Paulisa Siddhanta texts depict the influence of Greek astronomical ideas on Indian astronomy.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Following the conquests of Alexander the Great in the east, Hellenistic influence on Indian art was far-reaching.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In architecture, a few examples of the Ionic order can be found as far as Pakistan with the Jandial temple near Taxila.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Several examples of capitals displaying Ionic influences can be seen as far as Patna, especially with the Pataliputra capital, dated to the 3rd century BC.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Corinthian order is also heavily represented in the art of Gandhara, especially through Indo-Corinthian capitals.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander and his exploits were admired by many Romans, especially generals, who wanted to associate themselves with his achievements.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Polybius began his *Histories* by reminding Romans of Alexander's achievements, and thereafter Roman leaders saw him as a role model.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey the Great adopted the epithet "Magnus" and even Alexander's anastole-type haircut, and searched the conquered lands of the east for Alexander's 260-year-old cloak, which he then wore as a sign of greatness.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar dedicated a Lysippean equestrian bronze statue, but replaced Alexander's head with his own, while Octavian visited Alexander's tomb in Alexandria and temporarily changed his seal from a sphinx to Alexander's profile.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The emperor Trajan also admired Alexander, as did Nero and Caracalla.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macriani, a Roman family that in the person of Macrinus briefly ascended to the imperial throne, kept images of Alexander on their persons, either on jewellery or embroidered into their clothes.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] On the other hand, some Roman writers, particularly Republican figures, used Alexander as a cautionary tale of how autocratic tendencies can be kept in check by the values of the Roman Republic.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was used by these writers as an example of ruler values such as *amicitia* (friendship) and *clementia* (clemency), but also *iracundia* (anger) and *cupiditas gloriae* (over-desire for glory).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Emperor Julian in his satire called "The Caesars", describes a contest between the previous Roman emperors, with Alexander the Great called in as an extra contestant, in the presence of the assembled gods.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Itinerarium Alexandri is a 4th-century Latin description of Alexander the Great's campaigns.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar went to serve his quaestorship in Hispania after his wife's funeral, in the spring or early summer of 69 BC.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] While there, he encountered a statue of Alexander the Great, and realised with dissatisfaction that he was now at an age when Alexander had the world at his feet, while he had achieved comparatively little.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey posed as the "new Alexander" since he was his boyhood hero.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] After Caracalla concluded his campaign against the Alamanni, it became evident that he was inordinately preoccupied with Alexander the Great.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He began openly mimicking Alexander in his personal style.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In planning his invasion of the Parthian Empire, Caracalla decided to arrange 16,000 of his men in Macedonian-style phalanxes, despite the Roman army having made the phalanx an obsolete tactical formation.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The historian Christopher Matthew mentions that the term *Phalangarii* has two possible meanings, both with military connotations.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] As a consequence, the *Phalangarii* of Legio II Parthica may not have been pikemen, but rather standard battle line troops or possibly *Triarii*.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Caracalla's mania for Alexander went so far that Caracalla visited Alexandria while preparing for his Persian invasion and persecuted philosophers of the Aristotelian school based on a legend that Aristotle had poisoned Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This was a sign of Caracalla's increasingly erratic behaviour.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] But this mania for Alexander, strange as it was, was overshadowed by subsequent events in Alexandria.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In AD 39, Caligula performed a spectacular stunt by ordering a temporary floating bridge to be built using ships as pontoons, stretching for over two miles from the resort of Baiae to the neighbouring port of Puteoli.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] It was said that the bridge was to rival the Persian king Xerxes' pontoon bridge crossing of the Hellespont.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula, who could not swim, then proceeded to ride his favourite horse Incitatus across, wearing the breastplate of Alexander the Great.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This act was in defiance of a prediction by Tiberius's soothsayer Thrasyllus of Mendes that Caligula had "no more chance of becoming emperor than of riding a horse across the Bay of Baiae".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The diffusion of Greek culture and language cemented by Alexander's conquests in West Asia and North Africa served as a "precondition" for the later Roman expansion into these territories and entire basis for the Byzantine Empire, according to Errington.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander wrote and received numerous letters, but no originals survive.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] A few official letters addressed to the Greek cities survive in copies inscribed in stone and the content of others is sometimes reported in historical sources.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] These only occasionally quote the letters and it is an open question how reliable such quotations are.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Several fictitious letters, some perhaps based on actual letters, made their way into the *Romance* tradition.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of the legends about Alexander derive from his own lifetime, probably encouraged by Alexander himself.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His court historian Callisthenes portrayed the sea in Cilicia as drawing back from him in proskynesis.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Writing shortly after Alexander's death, Onesicritus invented a tryst between Alexander and Thalestris, queen of the mythical Amazons.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In the first centuries after Alexander's death, probably in Alexandria, a quantity of the legendary material coalesced into a text known as the *Alexander Romance*, later falsely ascribed to Callisthenes and therefore known as *Pseudo-Callisthenes*.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This text underwent over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations throughout the Islamic and European worlds in premodern times, containing many dubious stories, and was translated into twenty-five languages, for example Middle Persian, Syriac and Arabic.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander the Great's accomplishments and legacy have been depicted in many cultures.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander has featured in both high and popular culture, beginning from his own era to the present day.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The *Alexander Romance*, in particular, has had a significant impact on portrayals of Alexander in later cultures, from Persian to medieval European, to modern Greek.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander features prominently in modern Greek folklore, more than any other ancient figure.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The colloquial form of his name in modern Greek ("O Megalexandros") is a household name, and he is the only ancient hero to appear in the Karagiozis shadow play.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] One well-known fable among Greek seamen involves a solitary mermaid who would grasp a ship's prow during a storm and ask the captain, "Is King Alexander alive?" The answer should be "He is alive and well and rules the world!" causing the mermaid to vanish and the sea to calm.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Any other answer would cause the mermaid to turn into a raging Gorgon who would drag the ship to the bottom of the sea, all hands aboard.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In pre-Islamic Middle Persian (Zoroastrian) literature, Alexander is referred to by the epithet *gujastak*, meaning "accursed", and is accused of destroying temples and burning the sacred texts of Zoroastrianism.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In Islamic Persia, under the influence of the *Alexander Romance* (in Persian: اسکندرنامه *Iskandarnameh*), a more positive portrayal of Alexander emerges.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Firdausi's *Shahnameh* ("The Book of Kings") includes Alexander in a line of legitimate Persian shahs, a mythical figure who explored the far reaches of the world in search of the Fountain of Youth.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In the *Shahnameh*, Alexander's first journey is to Mecca to pray at the Kaaba.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was depicted as performing a Hajj (pilgrimage to Mecca) many times in subsequent Islamic art and literature.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Later Persian writers associate him with philosophy, portraying him at a symposium with figures such as Socrates, Plato and Aristotle, in search of immortality.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure of Dhu al-Qarnayn (Arabic: ذو القرنين; lit.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] 'The Two-Horned One') is believed by the majority of modern researchers of the Qur'an as well as Islamic commentators to be a reference to Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure is also believed by scholars to be based on later legends of Alexander.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In this tradition, he was a heroic figure who built a wall to defend against the nations of Gog and Magog.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] He also travelled the known world in search of the Water of Life and Immortality, eventually becoming a prophet.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The Syriac version of the *Alexander Romance* portrays him as an ideal Christian world conqueror who prayed to "the one true God".
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In Egypt, Alexander was portrayed as the son of Nectanebo II, the last pharaoh before the Persian conquest.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] His defeat of Darius was depicted as Egypt's salvation, "proving" Egypt was still ruled by an Egyptian.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Josephus, Alexander was shown the Book of Daniel when he entered Jerusalem, which described a mighty Greek king who would conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] This is cited as a reason for sparing Jerusalem.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In Hindi and Urdu, the name "Sikandar", derived from the Persian name for Alexander, denotes a rising young talent, and the Delhi Sultanate ruler Alauddin Khalji stylized himself as "Sikandar-i-Sani" (the Second Alexander the Great).
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] In medieval Europe, Alexander the Great was revered as a member of the Nine Worthies; a group of heroes whose lives were believed to encapsulate all the ideal qualities of chivalry.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] During the first Italian campaign of the French Revolutionary Wars, in a question from Bourrienne, asking whether he gave his preference to Alexander or Caesar, Napoleon said that he places Alexander The Great in the first rank, the main reason being his campaign on Asia.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Apart from a few inscriptions and fragments, texts written by people who actually knew Alexander or who gathered information from men who served with Alexander were all lost.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Contemporaries who wrote accounts of his life included Alexander's campaign historian Callisthenes, Alexander's generals; Ptolemy and Nearchus, Aristobulus, a junior officer on the campaigns, and Onesicritus, Alexander's chief helmsman.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Their works are lost, but later works based on these original sources have survived.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] The earliest of these is Diodorus Siculus (1st century BC), followed by Quintus Curtius Rufus (mid-to-late 1st century AD), Arrian (1st to 2nd century AD), the biographer Plutarch (1st to 2nd century AD), and finally Justin, whose work dated as late as the 4th century.
[src:battering-ram/alexander-the-great-p02] Of these, Arrian is generally considered the most reliable, given that he used Ptolemy and Aristobulus as his sources, closely followed by Diodorus.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Carthage was settled around 814 BC by merchants from Tyre, a leading Phoenician city-state located in present-day Lebanon.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] In the 7th century BC, following Phoenicia's conquest by the Neo-Assyrian Empire, Carthage became independent of its eastern neighbors.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Leveraging its naval power, Carthage then began to grow a vast patchwork of colonies, vassals, and satellite states until it was the economic and political hegemon of the western Mediterranean.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] By 300 BC, Carthage controlled the coast of northwestern Africa, southern and eastern Iberia, and the islands of Sicily, Sardinia, Corsica, Malta, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Tripoli remained *de facto* autonomous under the authority of local Libyco-Phoenicians, a mixed culture of local Libyans and Phoenicians, who paid nominal tribute.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Among the ancient world's largest and richest cities, Carthage's strategic location provided access to abundant fertile land and major maritime trade routes that reached West Asia and Northern Europe.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] This commercial empire was secured by one of the largest and most powerful navies in classical antiquity, and an army composed heavily of foreign mercenaries and auxiliaries, which included Iberians, Balearics, Gauls, Britons, Sicilians, Italians, Greeks, Numidians, and Libyans.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Carthage's unique system of government combined at different times elements of primitive democracy, oligarchy, and republicanism, including early examples of separation of powers.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] As the dominant power in the western Mediterranean, Carthage inevitably came into conflict with many neighbours and rivals, from the Berbers of North Africa to the nascent Roman Republic.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Following centuries of conflict with the Sicilian Greeks, its growing competition with Rome culminated in the Punic Wars (264–146 BC), which saw some of the largest and most sophisticated battles in antiquity.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Carthage narrowly avoided destruction after the Second Punic War, but was destroyed by the Romans in 146 BC after the Third Punic War.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] The Romans later founded a new city in its place.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] All remnants of Carthaginian civilization came under Roman rule by the 1st century AD, and Rome subsequently became the dominant Mediterranean power, paving the way for the Roman Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Despite having been one of the most influential civilizations of antiquity, Carthage is mostly remembered for its long and bitter conflict with Rome.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Due to the destruction of virtually all Carthaginian texts after the Third Punic War, much of what is known about its civilization comes from Roman and Greek sources, many of which were written during or after the Punic Wars, and to varying degrees were influenced by the hostilities.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Popular and scholarly attitudes towards Carthage historically reflected the prevailing Greco-Roman view, though archaeological research since the late 19th century has helped shed more light and nuance on Carthaginian civilization.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] The name *Carthage* /ˈkɑːrθɪdʒ/ is the Early Modern anglicisation of Middle French *Carthage* /kar.taʒ/, from Latin *Carthāgō* and *Karthāgō* (cf.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Greek *Karkhēdōn* (Καρχηδών) and Etruscan **Carθaza*) from the Punic *qrt-ḥdšt*, vocalised by Brett Mulligan as *Qart-Ḥadašt* (Punic: 𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤟𐤇𐤃𐤔𐤕, lit.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] It is unclear what term, if any, the Carthaginians used to refer to themselves.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Ancient Egyptian accounts suggest the people from the region identified as *Kenaani* or *Kinaani*, equivalent to Canaanite.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] A passage from Augustine claims that if asked, the people of Africa (modern day Tunisia) would reply that they are *Chanani* (Canaanites) in Phoenician.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] Despite that being almost universally accepted by scholars, some still dismiss Augustine's claims.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-carthage] For example, Josephine Quinn doubts the claim's truthfulness.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Well-known ancient artwork and sculptures, each representing a certain civilisation.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] The three-age system periodises ancient history into the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age, with recorded history usually considered to begin with the Bronze Age.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] The start and end of the three ages vary between world regions.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] In many regions the Bronze Age is generally considered to begin a few centuries prior to 3000 BC, while the end of the Iron Age varies from the early first millennium BC in some regions to the late first millennium AD in others.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] During the time period of ancient history, the world population was exponentially increasing due to the Neolithic Revolution, which was in full progress.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] In 10,000 BC, the world population stood at an estimated 2 million, it rose to 45 million by 3000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] By the Iron Age in 1000 BC, the population had risen to 72 million.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] By the end of the ancient period in AD 500, the world population is thought to have stood at 209 million.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] In 10,500 years, the world population increased by 100 times.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Prehistory is the period before written history.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Most of the knowledge of that period comes from the work of archaeologists.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] The early human migrations in the Lower Paleolithic saw *Homo erectus* spread across Eurasia 1.8 million years ago.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for the use of fire has been dated as early as 1.8 million years ago, a date which is contested, with generally accepted evidence for the controlled use of fire dating to 780,000 years ago.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Actual use of hearths first appears 400,000 years ago.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Dates for the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (modern humans) range from 250,000 to 160,000 years ago, with the varying dates being based on DNA studies and fossils respectively.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Some 50,000 years ago, *Homo sapiens* migrated out of Africa.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] They reached Australia about 45,000 years ago, southwestern Europe about the same time, southeastern Europe and Siberia around 40,000 years ago, and Japan about 30,000 years ago.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Humans migrated to the Americas about 15,000 years ago.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for agriculture emerges in about 9000 BC in what is now eastern Turkey and spread through the Fertile Crescent.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Settlement at Göbekli Tepe began around 9500 BC and may have the world's oldest temple.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] The Nile River Valley has evidence of sorghum and millet cultivation starting around 8000 BC and agricultural use of yams in Western Africa perhaps dates to the same time period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Cultivation of millet, rice, and legumes began around 7000 BC in China.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Taro cultivation in New Guinea dates to about 7000 BC also with squash cultivation in Mesoamerica perhaps sharing that date.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Animal domestication began with the domestication of dogs, which dates to at least 15,000 years ago, and perhaps even earlier.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Sheep and goats were domesticated around 9000 BC in the Fertile Crescent, alongside the first evidence for agriculture.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Other animals, such as pigs and poultry, were later domesticated and used as food sources.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Cattle and water buffalo were domesticated around 7000 BC and horses, donkeys, and camels were domesticated by about 4000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] All of these animals were used not only for food, but to carry and pull people and loads, greatly increasing human ability to do work.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] The invention of the simple plough by 6000 BC further increased agricultural efficiency.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Metal use in the form of hammered copper items predates the discovery of smelting of copper ores, which happened around 6000 BC in western Asia and independently in eastern Asia before 2000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Gold and silver use dates to between 6000 and 5000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Alloy metallurgy began with bronze in about 3500 BC in Mesopotamia and was developed independently in China by 2000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Pottery developed independently throughout the world, with fired pots appearing first among the Jomon of Japan and in West Africa at Mali.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Sometime between 5000 and 4000 BC the potter's wheel was invented.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] By 3000 BC, the pottery wheel was adapted into wheeled vehicles which could be used to carry loads further and easier than with human or animal power alone.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Writing developed separately in five different locations in human history: Mesopotamia, Egypt, India, China, and Mesoamerica.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] By 3400 BC, "proto-literate" cuneiform spread in the Middle East.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Egypt developed its own system of hieroglyphs by about 3200 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] By 2800 BC the Indus Valley Civilisation had developed its Indus script, which remains undeciphered.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Chinese Characters were independently developed in China during the Shang dynasty in the form of the Oracle Bone Script dating to the period 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p01] Writing in Mesoamerica dates to 600 BC with the Zapotec civilization.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The ancient Near East is considered the cradle of civilisation.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It began the study of the stars and the sciences of astronomy and mathematics.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Mesopotamia is the site of some of the earliest known civilisations in the world.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural communities emerged in the area with the Halaf culture around 8000 BC and continued to expand through the Ubaid period around 6000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Cities began in the Uruk period (4000–3100 BC) and expanded during the Jemdet Nasr (3100–2900 BC) and Early Dynastic (2900–2350 BC) periods.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The surplus of storable foodstuffs created by this economy allowed the population to settle in one place instead of migrating after crops and herds.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It also allowed for a much greater population density, and in turn required an extensive labour force and division of labour.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This organisation led to the necessity of record keeping and the development of writing.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia was an Amorite state in lower Mesopotamia (modern southern Iraq), with Babylon as its capital.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia emerged when Hammurabi created an empire out of the territories of the former kingdoms of Sumer and Akkad.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire, or Chaldea, was Babylonia from the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Under the reign of Nebuchadnezzar II, it conquered Jerusalem.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This empire also created the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the still-surviving Ishtar Gate as architectural embellishments of its capital at Babylon.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Akkad was a city and its surrounding region near Babylon.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Akkad also became the capital of the Akkadian Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Despite an extensive search, the precise site has never been found.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Akkad reached the height of its power between about 2330 and 2150 BC, following the conquests of King Sargon of Akkad.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Through the spread of Sargon's empire, the language of Akkad, known as Akkadian from the city, spread and replaced the Sumerian language in Mesopotamia and eventually by 1450 BC was the main language of diplomacy in the Near East.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Assyria was originally a region on the Upper Tigris, where a small state was created in the 19th century BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The capital was at Assur, which gave the state its name.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Later, as a nation and empire that came to control all of the Fertile Crescent, Egypt, and much of Anatolia, the term "Assyria proper" referred to roughly the northern half of Mesopotamia (the southern half being Babylonia), with Nineveh as its capital.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Assyrian kings controlled a large kingdom at three different times in history.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These are called the *Old* (20th to 18th centuries BC), *Middle* (14th to 11th centuries BC), and *Neo-Assyrian* (9th to 7th centuries BC) kingdoms, or periods.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Mitanni was a Hurrian empire in northern Mesopotamia founded around 1500 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Mitanians conquered and controlled Assyria until the 14th century BC while contending with Egypt for control of parts of modern Syria.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Its capital was Washukanni, whose precise location has not been determined by archaeologists.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Medes and Persians were peoples who had appeared in the Iranian plateau around 1500 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Both peoples spoke Indo-European languages and were mostly pastoralists with a tradition of horse archery.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Medes established their own Median Empire by the 6th century BC, having defeated the Neo-Assyrian Empire with the Chaldeans in 614 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid Empire was founded by Cyrus the Great, who first became king of the Persians, then conquered the Medes, Lydia, and Babylon by 539 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The empire built on earlier Mesopotamian systems of government to govern their large empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By building roads, they improved both the ability to send governmental instructions throughout their lands as well as improving the ability of their military forces to be deployed rapidly.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Increased trade and upgraded farming techniques increased wealth, but also exacerbated inequalities between social classes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The empire's location at the centre of trading networks spread its intellectual and philosophical ideas throughout a wide area, and its religion, while not itself spreading far, had an impact on later religions such as Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Cyrus' son Cambyses II conquered Egypt, while a later emperor, Darius the Great, expanded the empire to the Indus River, creating the largest empire in the world to that date.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] But Darius and his son Xerxes I failed to expand into Greece, with expeditions in 490 and 480 BC eventually failing.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid dynasty and empire fell to Alexander the Great by 330 BC, and after Alexander's death, much of the area previously ruled by the Cyrus and his successors was ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Parthia was an Iranian civilisation situated in the northeastern part of modern Iran.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Their power was based on a combination of military power based on heavy cavalry with a decentralised governing structure based on a federated system.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Parthian Empire was led by the Arsacid dynasty, which by around 155 BC under Mithradates I had mostly conquered the Seleucid Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Parthia had many wars with the Romans, but it was rebellions within the empire that ended it in the 3rd century AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Sasanian Empire began when the Parthian Empire ended in AD 224.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Their rulers claimed the Achaemenids as ancestors and set up their capital at Ctesiphon in Mesopotamia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Their period of greatest military expansion occurred under Shapur I, who by the time of his death in AD 272 had defeated Roman imperial armies and set up buffer states between the Sasanians and Roman Empires.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After Shapur, the Sasanians were under more pressure from the Kushans to their east as well as the Roman then Byzantine Empire to its west.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] However, the Sasanians rebuilt and founded numerous cities and their merchants travelled widely and introduced crops such as sugar, rice, and cotton into the Iranian plateau.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] But in AD 651, the last Sassanid emperor was killed by the expanding Islamic Arabs.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites first came to Anatolia about 1900 BC and during the period 1600–1500 they expanded into Mesopotamia where they adopted the cuneiform script to their Indo-European language.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By 1200 their empire stretched to Phoenicia and eastern Anatolia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] They improved two earlier technologies from Mesopotamia and spread these new techniques widely – improved iron working and light chariots with spoked wheels in warfare.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites introduced the casting of iron with molds and then hammering it which enabled weapons and tools to be made stronger and also cheaper.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Although chariots had been used previously, the use of spoked wheels allowed the chariots to be much lighter and more maneuverable.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In 1274 BC the Hittites clashed with the Egyptians at the Battle of Kadesh, where both sides claimed victory.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In 1207 BC the Hittite capital of Hattusa was sacked, ending the Hittite Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Israel and Judah were related Iron Age kingdoms of the ancient Levant and had existed during the Iron Ages and the Neo-Babylonian, Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The name Israel first appears in the stele of the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah around 1209 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This "Israel" was a cultural and probably political entity of the central highlands, well enough established to be perceived by the Egyptians as a possible challenge to their hegemony, but an ethnic group rather than an organised state.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Israel had emerged by the middle of the 9th century BC, when the Assyrian King Shalmaneser III named "Ahab the Israelite" among his enemies at the battle of Qarqar (853).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Judah emerged somewhat later than Israel, probably during the 9th century BC, but the subject is one of considerable controversy.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Israel came into conflict with the Assyrians, who conquered Israel in 722 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire did the same to Judah in 586.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After both conquests, the conquering forces deported many of the inhabitants to other regions of their respective empires.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Phoenicia was an ancient civilisation centred in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coastal regions of modern-day Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Phoenician civilisation was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean between the period of 1550 to 300 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] One Phoenician colony, Carthage, ruled an empire in the Western Mediterranean until being defeated by Rome in the Punic Wars.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Phoenicians invented the Phoenician alphabet, the forerunner of the modern alphabet still in use today.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The history of Pre-Islamic Arabia before the rise of Islam in the AD 630s is not known in great detail.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Archaeological exploration in the Arabian Peninsula has been sparse; indigenous written sources are limited to the many inscriptions and coins from southern Arabia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Existing material consists primarily of written sources from other traditions (such as Egyptians, Greeks, Persians, Romans, etc.) and oral traditions later recorded by Islamic scholars.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] A number of small kingdoms existed in Arabia from around AD 100 to perhaps about AD 400.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt was a long-lived civilisation geographically located in north-eastern Africa.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It was concentrated along the middle to lower reaches of the Nile River, reaching its greatest extent during the 2nd millennium BC, which is referred to as the New Kingdom period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It reached broadly from the Nile Delta in the north, as far south as Jebel Barkal at the Fourth Cataract of the Nile.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Extensions to the geographical range of ancient Egyptian civilisation included, at different times, areas of the southern Levant, the Eastern Desert and the Red Sea coastline, the Sinai Peninsula, and the Western Desert (focused on the several oases).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt developed over at least three and a half millennia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It began with the incipient unification of Nile Valley polities around 3100 BC, traditionally under Menes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Overseeing these activities were a socio-political and economic elite under the figure of a (semi)-divine ruler from a succession of ruling dynasties.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egyptian history is divided across various periods, beginning with the Old Kingdom, which saw pyramid building on a large scale.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After 2100 BC, the Old Kingdom dissolved into smaller states during the First Intermediate Period, which lasted about 100 years.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom began around 2000 BC with the reunification of Egypt under pharoes ruling from Thebes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom ended with the conquest of northern Egypt by the Hyksos around 1650 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Hyksos were expelled from Egypt and the land was reunited in the New Kingdom around 1550 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This period lasted until about 1000 BC, and saw Egypt expand its borders into Palestine and Syria.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Third Intermediate Period was marked by the rule of priests as well as the conquest of Egypt by Nubian kings and then later Assyria, Persia, and Macedonians.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Carthage was founded around 814 BC by Phoenician settlers.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Carthage was a city-state that ruled an empire through alliances and trade influence that stretched throughout North Africa and modern Spain.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] At the height of the city's influence, its empire included most of the western Mediterranean.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The empire was in a constant state of struggle with the Roman Republic, which led to a series of conflicts known as the Punic Wars.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After the third and final Punic War, Carthage was destroyed and then occupied by Roman forces.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Nearly all of the territory held by Carthage fell into Roman hands.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Ta-Seti kingdom in Nubia to the south of Egypt was conquered by Egyptian rulers around 3100 BC, but by 2500 BC the Nubians had created a new kingdom further south, known as the Kingdom of Kush, centred on the upper Nile with a capital at Kerma.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In the Egyptian New Kingdom period, Kush once more was conquered by Egypt.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] However, by 1100 BC a new kingdom of Kush had formed, with a capital at Napata.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Nubian rulers conquered Egypt around 760 BC and retained control for about a century.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum was an important trading nation in northeastern Africa centred in present-day Eritrea and northern Ethiopia, it existed from approximately AD 100 to 940, growing from the Iron Age proto-Aksumite period around the 4th century BC to achieve prominence by the 1st century AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum at its height by the early 6th-century AD extended through much of modern Ethiopia and across the Red Sea to Arabia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The capital city of the empire was Aksum, now in northern Ethiopia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Nok culture appeared in Nigeria around 1000 BC and mysteriously vanished around AD 200.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation's social system is thought to have been highly advanced.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Nok civilisation was considered to be the earliest sub-Saharan producer of life-sized Terracotta which have been discovered by archaeologists.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Nok also used iron smelting that may have been independently developed.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation of Djenné-Djenno was located in the Niger River Valley in the country of Mali and is considered to be among the oldest urbanised centres and the best-known archaeology site in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This archaeological site is located about 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) away from the modern town and is believed to have been involved in long-distance trade and possibly the domestication of African rice.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The site is believed to exceed 33 hectares (82 acres); however, this is yet to be confirmed with extensive survey work.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] With the help of archaeological excavations mainly by Susan and Roderick McIntosh, the site is known to have been occupied from 250 BC to AD 900.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The city is believed to have been abandoned and moved where the current city is located due to the spread of Islam and the building of the Great Mosque of Djenné.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Previously, it was assumed that advanced trade networks and complex societies did not exist in the region until the arrival of traders from Southwest Asia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] However, sites such as Djenné-Djenno disprove this, as these traditions in West Africa flourished long before.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Towns similar to that at Djenne-Jeno also developed at the site of Dia, also in Mali along the Niger River, from around 900 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Dhar Tichitt and Oualata were prominent among the early urban centres, dated to 2000 BC, in present-day Mauritania.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] About 500 stone settlements littered the region in the former savannah of the Sahara.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It has been found that the Soninke of the Mandé peoples were responsible for constructing such settlements.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Around 300 BC, the region became more desiccated and the settlements began to decline, most likely relocating to Koumbi Saleh.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] From the type of architecture and pottery, it is believed that Tichit was related to the subsequent Ghana Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Old Jenne (Djenne) began to be settled around 300 BC, producing iron and with sizeable population, evidenced in crowded cemeteries.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The inhabitants and creators of these settlements during these periods are thought to have been ancestors of the Soninke people.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Peoples speaking precursors to the modern-day Bantu languages began to spread throughout southern Africa, and by 2000 BC they were expanding past the Congo River and into the Great Lakes area.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By AD 1000 these groups had spread throughout all of southern Africa south of the equator.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Iron metallurgy and agriculture spread along with these peoples, with the cultivation of millet, oil palms, sorghum, and yams as well as the use of domesticated cattle, pigs, and sheep.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These technologies helped increase population, and settled communities became common in sub-Saharan Africa except in deserts or heavy forests.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Paleolithic tools have been discovered in India dating to 200,000 years ago, and Neolithic sites are known from near the Indus Valley dating to around 8000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Agriculture began in the Indus Valley around 7000 BC, and reached the Ganges Valley by 3000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Barley, cotton, and wheat were grown and the population had domesticated cattle, goats, and sheep.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Indus Valley Civilisation developed around 3000 BC in the Indus and Ghaggar-Hakra river valleys of north-east Afghanistan, Pakistan, and western India.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Another name for this civilisation is Harappan, after the first of its cities to be excavated, Harappa (now in the Pakistani province of Punjab).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Harappan civilisation grew out of the earlier agricultural communities as they evolved into cities.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These communities created and traded jewelry, figurines, and seals that appear widely scattered throughout Mesopotamia, Afghanistan, and Iran.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Chickens were domesticated in addition to the earlier crops and animals.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] They developed their own writing system, the Indus Valley script, which is still mostly undeciphered.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The exact structure of society and the way the cities were governed is not known.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By about 1600 BC, the Indus Valley culture had abandoned many of their cities, including Mohenjo-Daro.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The exact reason for this decline is not known.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Indo-European speaking peoples began to spread into India about 1500 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The *Rigveda*, in Sanskrit, dates to this period and begins a period often known as the Vedic period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Between 1500 and 500 BC these peoples spread throughout most of India and had begun to found small cities.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Vedic society was characterised by the *varna* system which divided society into four broad castes, which were later elaborated.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By the end of the Vedic period, this way of organising society had become central to Indian society.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Religion in the late Vedic period was evolving into Hinduism, which spread throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Siddhartha Gautama, born around 560 BC in northern India, went on to found a new religion based on his ascetic life – Buddhism.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This faith also spread throughout Eastern and Southeastern Asia after his death.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This period also saw the composition of the epics *Ramayana* and *Mahabharata*.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The kingdom of Magadha rose to prominence under a number of dynasties that peaked in power under the reign of Ashoka Maurya, one of India's most legendary and famous emperors.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] During the reign of Ashoka, the four dynasties of Chola, Chera, and Pandya were ruling in the South, while Devanampiya Tissa (250–210 BC) controlled Anuradhapura (now Sri Lanka).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These kingdoms, while not part of Ashoka's empire, were in friendly terms with the Maurya Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] An alliance existed between Devanampiya Tissa and Ashoka of India, who sent Buddhist missionaries to Sri Lanka.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Most of North India was reunited under the Gupta Empire beginning under Chandragupta I around AD 320.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Under his successors the empire spread to include much of India except for the Deccan Plateau and the very south of the peninsula.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This was a period of relative peace, and the Gupta rulers generally left administration in local rulers.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Gupta Empire was weakened and ultimately ruined by the raids of Hunas (a branch of the Hephthalites emanating from Central Asia), and the empire broke up into smaller regional kingdoms by the end of the fifth century AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] India would remain fragmented into smaller states until the rise of the Mughal Empire in the 1500s.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Neolithic period of Southeast Asia was characterised by several migrations into Mainland and Island Southeast Asia from southern China by Austronesian, Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Hmong–Mien speakers.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Territorial principalities in both Insular and Mainland Southeast Asia, characterised as "agrarian kingdoms", developed an economy by around 500 BC based on surplus crop cultivation and moderate coastal trade of domestic natural products.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Several states of the Malayan-Indonesian "thalassian" zone shared these characteristics with Indochinese polities like the Pyu city-states in the Irrawaddy River valley, the Văn Lang kingdom in the Red River Delta and Funan around the lower Mekong.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Văn Lang, founded in the 7th century BC, endured until 258 BC under the Hồng Bàng dynasty, as part of the Đông Sơn culture that sustained a dense and organised population that produced an elaborate Bronze Age industry.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Intensive wet-rice cultivation in an ideal climate enabled the farming communities to produce a regular crop surplus that was used by the ruling elite to raise, command and pay work forces for public construction and maintenance projects such as canals and fortifications.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The earliest known evidence of copper and bronze production in Southeast Asia was found at Ban Chiang in north-east Thailand and among the Phùng Nguyên culture of northern Vietnam around 2000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Đông Sơn culture established a tradition of bronze production and the manufacture of evermore refined bronze and iron objects, such as plows, axes and sickles with shaft holes, socketed arrows and spearheads and small ornamented items.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By about 500 BC, large and delicately decorated bronze drums of remarkable quality, weighing more than 70 kg (150 lb), were produced in the laborious lost-wax casting process.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This industry of highly sophisticated metal processing was developed independent of Chinese or Indian influence.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Historians relate these achievements to the presence of organised, centralised and hierarchical communities and a large population.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Between 1000 BC and 100 AD, the Sa Huỳnh culture flourished along the south-central coast of Vietnam.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ceramic jar burial sites that included grave goods have been discovered at various sites along the entire territory.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Among large, thin-walled terracotta jars, ornamented and colorized cooking pots, glass items, jade earrings and metal objects were deposited near the rivers and along the coast.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Around 3000 to 1500 BC, a large-scale migration of Austronesians, known as the Austronesian expansion began from Taiwan.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Population growth primarily fuelled this migration.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonised the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BC or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 AD, when there was another surge of island colonisation.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 AD; Hawaii by 900 AD; Rapa Nui by 1000 AD; and New Zealand by 1200 AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Austronesians established prehistoric maritime trade networks in Island Southeast Asia, including the Maritime Jade Road, a jade trade network, in Southeast Asia which existed in Taiwan and the Philippines from 2000 BC to 1000 AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The trade was established by links between the indigenous peoples of Taiwan and the Philippines, and later included parts of Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, and other areas in Southeast Asia (known as the Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Lingling-o artefacts are among the notable archaeological finds originating from the Maritime Jade Road.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] During the operation of the Maritime Jade Road, the Austronesian spice trade networks were also established by Islander Southeast Asians with Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1000 to 600 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BC, based on such archaeological evidence as banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Estimates for when this occurred vary from the 1st century AD to as late as the 6th to 7th centuries AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By around the 2nd century BC, the Neolithic Austronesian jade and spice trade networks in Southeast Asia connected with the maritime trade routes of South Asia, the Middle East, eastern Africa, and the Mediterranean, becoming what is now known as the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the 10th century, the eastern part of the route was primarily used by Southeast Asian Austronesian traders using distinctive lashed-lug ships, although Tamil and Persian traders also sailed the western parts of the routes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It allowed the exchange of goods from East and Southeast Asia on one end, all the way to Europe and eastern Africa on the other.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Srivijaya, an Austronesian polity founded at Palembang in 682 AD, rose to dominate the trade in the region around the straits of Malacca and Sunda and the South China Sea emporium by controlling the trade in luxury aromatics and Buddhist artefacts from West Asia to a thriving Tang market.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It emerged through the conquest and subjugation of neighbouring thalassocracies.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These included Melayu, Kedah, Tarumanagara, and Mataram, among others.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These polities controlled the sea lanes in Southeast Asia and exploited the spice trade of the Spice Islands, as well as maritime trade-routes between India and China.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Chinese civilisation that emerged within the Yellow River valley is one of earliest civilisations in the world.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the formation of civilisation, neolithic cultures such as the Longshan and Yangshao dating to 5000 BC produced sophisticated pottery, cultivated millet, and likely produced clothes woven from hemp and silk.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Rice was also farmed and pigs and water buffalo were kept for food.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Longshan potters may have used the pottery wheel to produce their wares.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Chinese traditions described three ancient dynasties that predated the unification under the Qin and Han dynasties.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These were the Xia, the Shang, and the Zhou.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] It was not until the later 20th century that many historians considered the Shang or Xia to be anything other than legendary.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Little is yet known about the Xia, which appears to have begun around 2200 BC, and may have controlled parts of the Yangtze River valley.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Shang dynasty traditionally is dated to 1766 to 1122 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Bronze was central to Shang culture and technology, with chariots and bronze weapons helping to expand Shang control over northern China.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The cities at Ao and Yinxu, near Anyang, have been excavated and city walls, royal palaces, and archives as well as tombs and workshops were found.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] A system of writing developed, beginning with oracle bones, of which over 100,000 are still extant.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Towards the end of the 2nd millennium BC, the Shang were overrun by the Zhou dynasty from the Wei River valley to the west.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou rulers at this time invoked the concept of the Mandate of Heaven to legitimize their rule, a concept that would be influential for almost every successive dynasty.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou initially established their capital in the west near modern Xi'an, near the Yellow River, but they would preside over a series of expansions into the Yangtze River valley.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Zhou administration was decentralised, with local elites responsible for collecting tribute and providing military support to the Zhou rulers.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In the 8th century BC, power became decentralized during the Spring and Autumn period, named after the influential *Spring and Autumn Annals*.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In this period, local military leaders used by the Zhou began to assert their power and vie for hegemony.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The situation was aggravated by the invasion of other peoples, forcing the Zhou to move their capital east to Luoyang.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In each of the hundreds of states that eventually arose, local strongmen held most of the political power and continued their subservience to the Zhou kings in name only.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Hundred Schools of Thought of Chinese philosophy blossomed during this period, and such influential intellectual movements as Confucianism, Taoism, Legalism and Mohism were founded, partly in response to the changing political world.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After further political consolidation, seven prominent states remained by the end of the 5th century BC, and the years in which these few states battled each other is known as the Warring States period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Though there remained a nominal Zhou king until 256 BC, he was largely a figurehead and held little power.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] As neighboring territories of these warring states, including areas of modern Sichuan and Liaoning, were annexed by the growing power of the rulers of Qin, they were governed under the new local administrative system of commandery.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The final expansion in this period began during the reign of Ying Zheng, the king of Qin.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] His unification of the other six powers, and further annexations to the south and southeast by 213 BC enabled him to proclaim himself the First Emperor (Qin Shi Huangdi).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Qin Shi Huangdi ruled the unified China directly with absolute power.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In contrast to the decentralised and feudal rule of earlier dynasties the Qin ruled directly.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Nationwide the philosophy of legalism was enforced and publications promoting rival ideas such as Confucianism were prohibited.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In his reign unified China created the first continuous Great Wall with the use of forced labour.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Invasions were launched southward to annex Vietnam.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Qin period also saw the standardisation of the Chinese writing system and the government unified the legal systems as well as setting standardised units of measurement throughout the empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After the emperor's death rebellions began and the Han dynasty took power and ruled China for over four centuries with a brief interruption from AD 9 to 23.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Han dynasty promoted the spread of iron agricultural tools, which helped create a food surplus that led to a large growth of population during the Han period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Silk production also increased and the manufacture of paper was invented.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Though the Han enjoyed great military and economic success, it was strained by the rise of aristocrats who disobeyed the central government.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Public frustration provoked the Yellow Turban Rebellion; though a failure it nonetheless accelerated the empire's downfall.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After AD 208, the Han dynasty broke up into rival kingdoms.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] China would remain divided for almost the next 400 years.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The East Asian nations adjacent to China were all profoundly influenced by their interactions with Chinese civilisation.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Northwestern Korea and Northern Vietnam were brought under Han rule by Han Wudi in the second century BC, and this rule led to cultural influences on both areas for many centuries to come.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Wudi also faced a threat from the Xiongnu, a nomadic people from the Central Asian steppes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Wudi's invasions ended the Xiongnu state.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In 108 BC, the Han dynasty of China conquered much of northern Korea but when Han China began its decline, three kingdoms in Korea – those of Baekje, Goguryeo and Silla – emerged and expelled the Chinese.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Goguryeo and Baekje were eventually destroyed by a Tang dynasty and Silla alliance.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Silla then drove out the Tang dynasty in 676 to control most of the Korean peninsula undisputed.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Jomon culture formed in Japan before 500 BC and under Chinese influence became the Yayoi culture which built large tombs by AD 200.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In the 300s, a kingdom formed in the Yamato plain, perhaps influenced by Korean refugees.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] In pre-Columbian times, several large, centralised ancient civilisations developed in the Western Hemisphere, both in Mesoamerica and western South America.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Beyond these areas, the use of agriculture expanded to the southwest of the continental United States by 1200 BC, and into the eastern woodlands of North America by AD 100.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Andean civilisation began with the rise of organised fishing communities from 3500 BC onwards.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Along with a sophisticated maritime society came the construction of large monuments, which likely existed as community centres.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The peoples of this area grew beans, cotton, peanuts, and sweet potatoes, fished in the ocean, and by about 2000 BC had added the potato to their crops.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Chavin culture, based around the Chavin cult, emerged around 1000 BC and led to large temples and artworks as well as sophisticated textiles.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Gold, silver, and copper were worked for jewelry and occasionally for small copper tools.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After the decline of Chavin culture, a number of cities formed after about 200 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The cities at Huari, Pucara, and Tiahuanaco were all likely over 10,000 residents.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] From about AD 300, the Mochica culture arose along the Moche River.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These people left painted pottery depicting their society and culture with a wide range of varied subjects.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Besides the Mochica, there were a number of other large states in the Andes after about AD 100.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Included amongst these are the Nazca culture, who were mainly village-dwelling but left behind a large ceremonial centre at Cahuachi as well as the Nazca lines, a large number of huge designs set into the desert floor.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural cultivation began around 8000 BC in Mesoamerica, where avocados, beans, chili peppers, gourds, and squashes were grown from about 7000 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Around 4000 BC maize began to be grown, and soon after this tomatoes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Settlements appeared around 3000 BC and by 2000 BC most of Mesoamerica was practicing agriculture.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Although some animals were domesticated — notably turkeys and dogs — the lack of suitable large animals precluded the development of animals used for transportation or labour.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Around 1200 BC the first Olmec centre of San Lorenzo was founded, which remained the centre of Olmec civilisation until around 800 BC when La Venta took over before losing primacy to Tres Zapotes around 400 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These and other Olmec centres were groups of tombs, temples, and other ceremonial sites built of stone.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Their construction testifies to the complexity of Olmec society, although the exact nature of how they were governed is not known.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] They also erected large stone sculptures of human heads and other subjects.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Jade jewelry and other Olmec objects are found throughout Mesoamerica, likely having travelled via trade networks.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Olmec writing system was mainly used for recording their calendar, both of which influenced later Mesoamerican cultures.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After the decline of the Olmecs, other civilisations in Mesoamerica either arose or emerged from the Olmec shadow - the Mayans, the Zapotecs, and Teotihuacan.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Zapotecs began around 500 BC in the Oaxaca Valley at the site of Monte Alban.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Monte Alban grew to around 25,000 residents in the period around AD 200, with the city having large stone temples and an expansive stone plaza.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Like the Olmecs, they had a writing system and calendar.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] But by AD 900 Monte Alban was deserted for unknown reasons.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Teotihuacan developed around AD 200 and centred on the city of Teotihuacan, which grew to perhaps as many as 200,000 inhabitants at its height.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Teotihuacan lasted until around AD 700, when it was burned and vandalised.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Maya culture began to emerge around AD 300 in the Yucatan Peninsula and modern-day Guatemala.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] During the 600 years of the Classical Maya period, more than 80 Mayan sites were built, with temples, pyramids, and palaces the focal point of each centre.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The most influential was Tikal, but Mayan civilisation was based on city-states which often were at war with each other.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This seems not to have restricted trade, which went on between the cities.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] A priestly elite kept astronomical and calendrical knowledge, recording it with a writing system based on the Olmec system of glyphs.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] History, poetry, and other records were recorded in books, most of which did not survive the Spanish conquest of Mesoamerica.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Mathematics was also studied, and they used the concept of zero in their calculations.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Mayan civilisation began to decline about AD 800, and most of its cities were deserted soon afterwards.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Organized societies, in the ancient United States or Canada, were often mound builder civilisations.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] One of the most significant of these was the Poverty Point culture that existed in the U.S. state of Louisiana, and was responsible for the creation of over 100 mound sites.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Mississippi River was a core area in the development of long-distance trade and culture.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Following Poverty Point, successive complex cultures such as the Hopewell emerged in the Southeastern United States in the Early Woodland period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Before AD 500 many mound builder societies retained a hunter gatherer form of subsistence.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Greece is home to the first advanced civilizations in Europe beginning with the Cycladic culture on the islands of the Aegean Sea around 3200 BC, and the Minoan civilisation in Crete (2700–1500 BC).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Minoans built large palaces decorated with frescoes and wrote in the undeciphered script known as Linear A.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Mycenaean civilization, the first distinctively Greek civilisation later emerged on the mainland (1600–1100 BC), consisting of a network of palace-centred states and writing the earliest attested form of Greek with the Linear B script.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Mycenaeans gradually absorbed the Minoans, but collapsed violently around 1200 BC, along with several other civilizations in the eastern Mediterranean, during the regional event known as the Late Bronze Age collapse.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This ushered in a period known as the Greek Dark Ages, from which written records are absent.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Archaic Period in Greece is generally considered to have lasted from around the 8th century BC to the invasion by Xerxes in 480 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This period saw the expansion of the Greek world around the Mediterranean, with the founding of Greek city-states as far afield as Sicily in the west and the Black Sea in the east.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Politically, the Archaic period in Greece saw the collapse of the power of the old aristocracies, with democratic reforms in Athens and the development of Sparta's unique constitution.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The end of the Archaic period also saw the rise of Athens, which would come to be a dominant power in the Classical Period, after the reforms of Solon and the tyranny of Pisistratus.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Classical Greek world was dominated throughout the 5th century BC by the major powers of Athens and Sparta.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The period in Greek history from the death of Alexander the Great until the rise of the Roman empire and its conquest of Egypt in 30 BC is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] After Alexander's death, a series of wars between his successors eventually led to three large states being formed from parts of Alexander's conquests, each ruled by a dynasty founded by one of the successors.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These were the Antigonids, the Selucids, and the Ptolemies.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These three kingdoms, along with smaller kingdoms, spread Greek culture and lifestyles into Asia and Egypt.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] These varying states eventually were conquered by Rome or the Parthian Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Rome was a civilisation that grew out of the city-state of Rome, originating as a small agricultural community founded on the Italian peninsula in the 8th century BC, with influences from Greece and other Italian civilisations, such as the Etruscans.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Traditionally Rome was founded as a monarchy that then became a republic.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Rome expanded through the Italian peninsula through a series of wars in the fifth through the third centuries BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] This expansion brought the Roman republic into conflict with Carthage, leading to a series of Punic Wars, that ended with the destruction of Carthage in 146 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Rome then expanded into Greece and the eastern Mediterranean, while a series of internal conflicts led to the republic becoming an empire ruled by an emperor by the first century AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Throughout the first and second centuries AD, the Empire grew slightly while spreading Roman culture throughout its boundaries.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] A number of factors led to the eventual decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Roman Empire underwent considerable social, cultural and organisational change starting with reign of Diocletian, who began the custom of splitting the empire into eastern and western halves ruled by multiple emperors.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Constantine the Great initiated the process of Christianisation of the empire and established a new capital at Constantinople.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Migrations of Germanic tribes disrupted Roman rule from the late 4th century onwards, culminating in the eventual collapse of the empire in the West in 476, replaced by the so-called barbarian kingdoms.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The resultant cultural fusion of Greco-Roman, Germanic and Christian traditions formed the cultural foundations of Europe.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] There has been attempt by scholars to connect European late antiquity to other areas in Eurasia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Celts were a diverse group of tribal societies in Iron Age Europe.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Proto-Celtic culture formed in the Early Iron Age in Central Europe (Hallstatt period, named for the site in present-day Austria).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By the later Iron Age (La Tène period), Celts had expanded over wide range of lands: as far west as Ireland and the Iberian Peninsula, as far east as Galatia (central Anatolia), and as far north as Scotland.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] By the early centuries AD, following the expansion of the Roman Empire and the Great Migrations of Germanic peoples, Celtic culture had become restricted to the British Isles.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Huns were a nomadic people who formed a large state in Eastern Europe by about AD 400, and under their leader Attila, they fought against both sections of the Roman Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] However, after Attila's death, the state fell apart and the Huns' influence in history disappeared.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Hun-Xiongnu connection is controversial at best and is often disputed but is also not completely discredited.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Migration of Germanic peoples to Britain from what is now northern Germany and southern Scandinavia is attested from the 5th century.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Groups of Goths migrated into western Europe, with the Ostrogoths eventually settling in Italy before being conquered by the Lombards.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] A related people, the Visigoths, settled in Spain, founding a kingdom that lasted until it was conquered by Islamic rulers in the AD 700s.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] Several Indo-european speaking peoples inhabited the Balkan peninsula including the Thracians and Illyrians, that were divided into many tribes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The first Illyrian tribe to create its own kingdom was the Enchelei, which formed its own state around the 8th-7th century BC and reached the height of their power under king Bardylis.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p02] The Ardiani were infamous for their piracy and wars against the Roman Empire, for the first time between 229 BC-228 BC, then for a second time during 220 BC-219 BC and for a third time during 168 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The rise of civilisation corresponded with the institutional sponsorship of belief in gods, supernatural forces and the afterlife.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] During the Bronze Age, many civilisations adopted their own form of polytheism.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Usually, polytheistic Gods manifested human personalities, strengths and failings.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Early religion was often based on location, with cities or entire countries selecting a deity, that would grant them preferences and advantages over their competitors.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Worship involved the construction of representation of deities, and the granting of sacrifices.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Sacrifices could be material goods, food, or in extreme cases human sacrifice to please a deity.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] New philosophies and religions arose in both east and west, particularly about the 6th century BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Over time, a great variety of religions developed around the world, with some of the earliest major ones being Hinduism (around 2000 BC), Buddhism (5th century BC), and Jainism (6th century BC) in India, and Zoroastrianism in Persia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Abrahamic religions trace their origin to Judaism, around 1700 BC.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] In the east, three schools of thought were to dominate Chinese thinking until the modern day.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] These were Taoism, Legalism and Confucianism.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Confucian tradition, which would attain dominance, looked for political morality not to the force of law but to the power and example of tradition.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Confucianism would later spread into the Korean peninsula and Japan.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] In the west, the Greek philosophical tradition, represented by Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle, was diffused throughout Europe and the Middle East in the 4th century BC by the conquests of Alexander the Great.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] After the Bronze and Iron Age religions formed, Christianity spread through the Roman world.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Ancient technological progress began before the recording of history, with tools, use of fire, domestication of animals, and agriculture all predating recorded history.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The use of metals and the ability to make metal alloys was foundational for later technologies to develop.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Medical knowledge, including the use of herbs to treat illnesses and wounds as well as some surgical techniques, advanced during antiquity.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] An early very important development that allowed for further advancement was writing, which allowed humans to record information for later use.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The characteristics of ancient Egyptian technology are indicated by a set of artifacts and customs that lasted for thousands of years.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Egyptians invented and used many basic machines, such as the ramp and the lever, to aid construction processes.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Egyptians also played an important role in developing Mediterranean maritime technology, including ships.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Babylonians and Egyptians were early astronomers who recorded their observations of the night sky.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] Water managing Qanats which likely emerged on the Iranian plateau and possibly also in the Arabian peninsula sometime in the early 1st millennium BC spread from there slowly west- and eastward.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-history-p03] The Hindu–Arabic numeral system with the concept of zero was developed in India, while modern forms of paper were invented in China in the first century AD.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The **ancient Near East** was home to many cradles of civilization, spanning Ancient Mesopotamia, the Ancient Levant, Ancient Egypt, Ancient Elam, Ancient Anatolia or Asia Minor, the Ancient South Caucasus and Armenian highlands, and Ancient Northern Arabia (including Dilmun).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] It is generally not considered to include Pre-Islamic Arabia as a whole or Ancient Nubia, though it is sometimes classified as encompassing Ancient Iran, and the Minoan, Mycenaean, and Cycladic civilizations.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Historically, the Near East denoted an area roughly encompassing central West Asia and Egypt, having been focused on the lands between Greece in the west and Iran in the east.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] It therefore largely corresponds with the modern-day geopolitical concept of the Middle East.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] It also saw the creation of the first writing system, the first alphabet (i.e., abjad), the first currency, and the first legal codes, all of which were monumental advances that laid the foundations of astronomy and mathematics, and the invention of the wheel.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] During this period, the region's previously stateless societies largely transitioned to building states, many of which gradually came to annex the territories of their neighbouring civilizations.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] This process continued until the entire ancient Near East was enveloped by militaristic empires that had emerged from their own lands to conquer and absorb a variety of cultures under the rule of a top-level government.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The phrase "ancient Near East" denotes the 19th-century distinction between the Near and Far East as global regions of interest to the British Empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The distinction began during the Crimean War.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The last major exclusive partition of the east between these two terms was current in diplomacy in the late 19th century, with the Hamidian massacres of the Armenians and Assyrians by the Ottoman Empire in 1894–1896 and the First Sino-Japanese War of 1894–1895.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The two theatres were described by the statesmen and advisors of the British Empire as "the Near East" and "the Far East".
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Shortly after, they were to share the stage with ''Middle East'', a term that came to prevail in the 20th century and continues in modern times.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] As *Near East* had meant the lands of the Ottoman Empire at roughly its maximum extent, on the fall of that empire, the use of Near East in diplomacy was reduced significantly in favor of the Middle East.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Meanwhile, the ancient Near East had become distinct.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The Ottoman rule over the Near East ranged from Vienna (to the north) to the tip of the Arabian Peninsula (to the south), from Egypt (in the west) to the borders of Iraq (in the east).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The 19th-century archaeologists added Iran to their definition, which was never under the Ottomans, but they excluded all of Europe and, generally, Egypt, which had parts in the empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Ancient Near East periodization is the attempt to categorize or divide time into discrete named blocks, or eras, of the Near East.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The result is a descriptive abstraction that provides a useful handle on Near East periods of time with relatively stable characteristics.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] 4000 to 3100 BC) existed from the protohistoric Chalcolithic to the early Bronze Age period in the history of Mesopotamia, following the Ubaid period.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Named after the Sumerian city of Uruk, this period saw the emergence of urban life in Mesopotamia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] It was followed by the Sumerian civilization in southern Mesopotamia.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The late Uruk period (3400 to 3200 BC) saw the gradual emergence of cuneiform script and corresponds to the early Bronze Age.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] Sumer hosted many early advances in human history, such as schools (c.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] 3000 BC), making the area a cradle of civilization.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The oldest excavated archaeological site in Sumer, Tell el-'Oueili, dates to the 7th millennium BC, although it is likely that the area was occupied even earlier.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The oldest layers at 'Oueili mark the beginning of the Ubaid period, which was followed by the Uruk period (4th millennium BC) and the Early Dynastic periods (3rd millennium BC).
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The Akkadian Empire, founded by Sargon the Great, lasted from the 24th to the 21st century BC, and was regarded by many as the world's first empire.
[src:battering-ram/ancient-middle-east] The Akkadians eventually fragmented into Assyria and Babylonia.
